1
00:00:37,998 --> 00:00:39,618
<i>MAN:
That's right.</i>

2
00:00:40,291 --> 00:00:41,921
<i>New York.</i>

3
00:00:42,252 --> 00:00:44,922
<i>It's 1958.</i>

4
00:00:45,797 --> 00:00:49,297
<i>Anyway, for a few more minutes it is.</i>

5
00:00:49,509 --> 00:00:53,259
<i>Come midnight, it's gonna be 1959.</i>

6
00:00:53,471 --> 00:00:57,481
<i>A whole other feeling. The new year.</i>

7
00:00:58,101 --> 00:00:59,601
<i>The future.</i>

8
00:01:00,770 --> 00:01:05,280
<i>Yeah, Old Daddy Earth fixing to start
one more trip around the sun.</i>

9
00:01:05,483 --> 00:01:09,323
<i>Everybody hoping this ride round
be a little more giddy...</i>

10
00:01:09,529 --> 00:01:11,569
<i>...a little more gay.</i>

11
00:01:11,781 --> 00:01:16,161
<i>Yup, all over town,
champagne corks is a-popping.</i>

12
00:01:16,369 --> 00:01:22,379
<i>Over in the Waldorf, the big shots is
dancing to the strains of Guy Lombardo.</i>

13
00:01:22,584 --> 00:01:28,554
<i>In Times Square, the little folks is watching
and waiting for that big ball to drop.</i>

14
00:01:29,174 --> 00:01:33,224
<i>They're all trying to catch hold
of one moment of time...</i>

15
00:01:33,428 --> 00:01:39,388
<i>...to be able to say,
"Right now! This is it! I got it!"</i>

16
00:01:39,601 --> 00:01:41,021
[CHUCKLES]

17
00:01:41,227 --> 00:01:43,647
<i>Of course, by then it'll be past.</i>

18
00:01:43,855 --> 00:01:49,275
<i>But they're all happy,
everybody having a good time.</i>

19
00:01:49,486 --> 00:01:52,196
<i>Well, almost everybody.</i>

20
00:01:52,405 --> 00:01:56,485
<i>There's a few lost souls
floating around out there.</i>

21
00:01:58,036 --> 00:02:00,536
<i>Now, if you all ain't from the city...</i>

22
00:02:00,747 --> 00:02:04,247
<i>...we got something here
called "the rat race. "</i>

23
00:02:04,459 --> 00:02:08,759
<i>Got a way of chewing folks up
so that they don't want no celebrating...</i>

24
00:02:08,963 --> 00:02:11,133
<i>...don't want no cheering up.</i>

25
00:02:11,341 --> 00:02:14,011
<i>Don't care nothing about no New Year's.</i>

26
00:02:14,677 --> 00:02:19,717
<i>Out of hope, out of rope, out of time.</i>

27
00:02:20,600 --> 00:02:23,600
<i>This here is Norville Barnes.</i>

28
00:02:24,562 --> 00:02:26,442
<i>That office he's stepping out of...</i>

29
00:02:26,648 --> 00:02:30,318
<i>...is the office of the president
of Hudsucker Industries.</i>

30
00:02:30,527 --> 00:02:32,447
<i>That's his office.</i>

31
00:02:33,404 --> 00:02:35,824
<i>How'd he get so high?</i>

32
00:02:36,032 --> 00:02:39,042
<i>And why's he feeling so low?</i>

33
00:02:39,869 --> 00:02:42,209
<i>Is he really going to do it?</i>

34
00:02:42,413 --> 00:02:46,583
<i>Is Norville really gonna
jelly up the sidewalk?</i>

35
00:02:47,418 --> 00:02:52,298
<i>Well, the future, that's something
you can never tell about.</i>

36
00:02:53,091 --> 00:02:56,471
<i>But the past, heh-heh...</i>

37
00:02:56,761 --> 00:02:59,561
<i>...that's another story.</i>

38
00:04:12,503 --> 00:04:14,423
[BUZZER SOUNDS]

39
00:05:15,900 --> 00:05:17,440
[BUZZER SOUNDS]

40
00:05:21,531 --> 00:05:23,661
In the third quarter
we saw no signs of weakening.

41
00:05:23,866 --> 00:05:26,946
We're up 18 percent over last year's
third-quarter gross...

42
00:05:27,161 --> 00:05:29,581
...and that, needless to say,
is a new record.

43
00:05:29,789 --> 00:05:34,379
Our competition continues to flag
and we continue to take up the slack.

44
00:05:34,585 --> 00:05:37,205
Market shares in most divisions
is increasing...

45
00:05:37,422 --> 00:05:40,722
...and we have opened
seven new regional offices.

46
00:05:40,925 --> 00:05:42,295
Our international division...

47
00:05:42,510 --> 00:05:46,640
...is also showing vigorous signs of upward
movement for the last six months...

48
00:05:46,848 --> 00:05:50,138
...and we're looking
at some exciting things in R&D.

49
00:06:30,308 --> 00:06:33,808
Sub-franchising.
Don't talk to me about sub-franchising.

50
00:06:34,020 --> 00:06:36,270
We're making so much money
in sub-franchising...

51
00:06:36,481 --> 00:06:38,151
...it isn't even funny.

52
00:06:38,358 --> 00:06:42,358
Our nominees and assigns
continue to multiply and expand...

53
00:06:42,570 --> 00:06:46,200
...extending our influence nationally
and abroad.

54
00:06:46,407 --> 00:06:48,697
Our owned
and operateds are performing...

55
00:06:48,910 --> 00:06:52,160
...far beyond our expectations
both here and abroad.

56
00:06:52,372 --> 00:06:54,922
And the Federal Tax Act of 1958...

57
00:06:55,124 --> 00:06:59,804
...is giving us a swell write-off
on our plant and heavies.

58
00:07:24,278 --> 00:07:28,368
And our last debenture issue
was this year's fastest seller.

59
00:07:28,574 --> 00:07:31,294
So third quarter and year-to-date...

60
00:07:31,494 --> 00:07:35,294
...we have set a new record in sales,
a new record in gross...

61
00:07:35,498 --> 00:07:38,168
...a new record in pre-tax earnings...

62
00:07:38,376 --> 00:07:41,456
...a new record in after-tax profits...

63
00:07:41,671 --> 00:07:44,551
...and our stock has split twice
in the past year.

64
00:07:44,757 --> 00:07:46,127
In short...

65
00:07:46,342 --> 00:07:47,842
[WATCH WINDING]

66
00:07:50,638 --> 00:07:52,518
...we're loaded.

67
00:07:52,723 --> 00:07:54,643
[ALL CHUCKLING]

68
00:07:54,851 --> 00:07:56,021
[TICKING]

69
00:07:59,814 --> 00:08:00,864
[CLEARS THROAT]

70
00:08:44,692 --> 00:08:46,362
Mr. Hudsucker?

71
00:08:46,569 --> 00:08:48,359
[CAR HORN HONKS]

72
00:09:11,844 --> 00:09:13,474
[SCREAMING]

73
00:09:41,791 --> 00:09:43,921
[SCREAMING]

74
00:09:44,126 --> 00:09:46,086
[BELL TOLLING]

75
00:10:31,924 --> 00:10:35,264
It's a pity to waste a whole Montecristo.

76
00:10:35,469 --> 00:10:36,849
He could've opened the window.

77
00:10:37,054 --> 00:10:39,774
Waring Hudsucker never did anything
the easy way.

78
00:10:39,974 --> 00:10:44,024
Why? Why did he do it?
Everything was going so well.

79
00:10:44,228 --> 00:10:47,108
What, am I a headshrinker?
Maybe the man was unhappy.

80
00:10:47,315 --> 00:10:49,145
[SOBBING]
He didn't look unhappy.

81
00:10:49,358 --> 00:10:53,818
- He didn't look rich.
- He was never an easy man to figure out.

82
00:10:54,030 --> 00:10:56,740
He built this company
with his bare hands.

83
00:10:56,949 --> 00:10:59,909
Every step he took was a step up...

84
00:11:00,244 --> 00:11:02,004
...except, of course, this last one.

85
00:11:02,204 --> 00:11:04,334
Sure, sure he was a swell fella...

86
00:11:04,540 --> 00:11:06,830
...but when the president,
chairman of the board...

87
00:11:07,001 --> 00:11:10,341
...and owner of 87 percent
of the company stock drops...

88
00:11:10,880 --> 00:11:12,800
...44 floors--
- Forty-five.

89
00:11:13,007 --> 00:11:14,217
Counting the mezzanine.

90
00:11:14,425 --> 00:11:17,135
Then the company, too,
has a problem. Stillson!

91
00:11:19,347 --> 00:11:21,927
What exactly is the disposition
of Waring's stock?

92
00:11:22,141 --> 00:11:23,561
Well, as you know...

93
00:11:23,768 --> 00:11:25,648
...Hud left no will and no family.

94
00:11:25,853 --> 00:11:28,733
The company bylaws
are quite clear in that event.

95
00:11:28,939 --> 00:11:32,359
"His entire portfolio will be converted
into common stock...

96
00:11:32,568 --> 00:11:36,908
...and will be sold over the counter
as of the first of the fiscal year...

97
00:11:37,114 --> 00:11:39,414
...following his demise."
- Meaning?

98
00:11:39,617 --> 00:11:43,117
Meaning simply that Waring's stock
and control of the company...

99
00:11:43,329 --> 00:11:46,789
...will be made available
to the public January 1st.

100
00:11:48,292 --> 00:11:49,672
Do you mean to say...

101
00:11:49,877 --> 00:11:53,507
...that any slob in a smelly T-shirt
will be able to buy Hudsucker stock?

102
00:11:54,131 --> 00:11:55,721
The company bylaws are quite clear.

103
00:11:55,925 --> 00:11:57,835
My God! You're animals!

104
00:11:58,052 --> 00:12:02,262
How can you discuss his stock
when the man has just leapt 45 floors?

105
00:12:02,473 --> 00:12:05,023
- Forty four.
- Not counting the mezzanine.

106
00:12:05,226 --> 00:12:07,266
Quit showboating, Addison.
The man is gone.

107
00:12:07,478 --> 00:12:10,648
The question now is whether
we'll let John Q. Public waltz in here...

108
00:12:10,856 --> 00:12:13,816
...and buy our company.
- What are you suggesting, Sydney?

109
00:12:14,026 --> 00:12:17,106
Certainly we can't afford
to buy a controlling interest.

110
00:12:17,321 --> 00:12:19,621
Not while the stock is this strong.

111
00:12:20,408 --> 00:12:22,908
How soon before Hud's paper
hits the market?

112
00:12:23,119 --> 00:12:24,289
- January 1st.
- Thirty days.

113
00:12:24,495 --> 00:12:26,155
- Four weeks.
- A month at the most.

114
00:12:26,372 --> 00:12:29,502
One month to make the blue-chip
investment of the century...

115
00:12:29,709 --> 00:12:32,089
...look like a round-trip ticket
on the Titanic.

116
00:12:32,294 --> 00:12:34,554
We play up the fact that Hud is dead.

117
00:12:34,755 --> 00:12:36,415
ALL:
Long live the Hud!

118
00:12:36,632 --> 00:12:39,592
- We depress the stock.
- To the point where we can buy 50 percent.

119
00:12:39,802 --> 00:12:41,802
- Fifty one.
- Not counting the mezzanine.

120
00:12:42,012 --> 00:12:43,392
- It could work.
- It should work.

121
00:12:43,597 --> 00:12:46,227
- It would work.
- It's working already.

122
00:12:47,435 --> 00:12:51,265
Waring Hudsucker is abstract art
on Madison Avenue.

123
00:12:51,480 --> 00:12:55,990
What we need now is a new president
who will inspire panic in the stockholder.

124
00:12:56,193 --> 00:12:57,493
"A Puppet.
'A proxy.

125
00:12:57,695 --> 00:12:59,105
MAN:
A pawn.

126
00:12:59,321 --> 00:13:02,581
Sure, sure, some jerk...

127
00:13:02,783 --> 00:13:05,163
...we can really push around.

128
00:13:06,579 --> 00:13:10,039
You punch in at 8:30 every morning,
at 7:30 following a business holiday...

129
00:13:10,249 --> 00:13:12,499
...unless it's a Monday,
then you punch in 8:00.

130
00:13:12,710 --> 00:13:15,920
- Punch in late and they dock you.
MAN: This goes to seven! Urgent.

131
00:13:16,130 --> 00:13:19,720
Incoming articles get a voucher.
Outgoing articles provide a voucher.

132
00:13:19,925 --> 00:13:22,335
Move any article without a voucher
and they dock you!

133
00:13:22,553 --> 00:13:24,973
Take this up to the secretarial pool
on three! ASAP!

134
00:13:25,181 --> 00:13:27,891
Letter-size, a green voucher!
Folder-size, a yellow voucher!

135
00:13:28,100 --> 00:13:31,310
- Parcel-size, a maroon voucher!
- This is for Morgatross! Chop-chop!

136
00:13:31,520 --> 00:13:34,520
Wrong color voucher and they dock you!

137
00:13:34,732 --> 00:13:37,112
6-7-8-7-0-4-9-Alpha-6!

138
00:13:37,318 --> 00:13:40,488
That is your employee number!
It will not be repeated!

139
00:13:40,696 --> 00:13:43,316
Without your employee number
you cannot get your paycheck.

140
00:13:43,532 --> 00:13:44,872
All right, this goes up to 27!

141
00:13:45,075 --> 00:13:47,865
Return a waiver!
Do not return without a signed waiver!

142
00:13:48,078 --> 00:13:52,288
Inter-office mail is code 37!
Intra-office mail is 37-3.

143
00:13:52,500 --> 00:13:54,670
Outside mail is 3-37.

144
00:13:54,877 --> 00:13:56,457
Code it wrong and they clock you!

145
00:13:56,670 --> 00:13:59,630
I was supposed to have this
on 2810 minutes ago!

146
00:13:59,840 --> 00:14:01,260
This has been your orientation.

147
00:14:01,467 --> 00:14:04,467
Is there anything you do not understand
or understand partially?

148
00:14:04,678 --> 00:14:08,348
If you have not been fully orientated,
you must file a complaint with Personnel!

149
00:14:08,557 --> 00:14:11,387
File a faulty complaint
and they clock you!

150
00:14:11,602 --> 00:14:14,062
[WHISTLING]

151
00:14:16,816 --> 00:14:20,736
Kloppitt. Kloppitt, Kloppitt...

152
00:14:20,945 --> 00:14:22,315
Max Kloppitt.

153
00:14:22,530 --> 00:14:24,660
"Max Kloppitt, Jr."

154
00:14:33,624 --> 00:14:36,754
What do you do when the envelope
is too big for the slot?

155
00:14:36,961 --> 00:14:40,211
Well, if you fold them, they fire you.

156
00:14:42,550 --> 00:14:44,680
I usually throw them out.

157
00:14:50,558 --> 00:14:52,888
- Just got hired today.
OLD MAN: Mm-hm.

158
00:14:53,102 --> 00:14:55,692
- Terrific.
NORVILLE: You know, entry level.

159
00:14:55,896 --> 00:14:57,606
OLD MAN:
Tell me about it.

160
00:14:58,440 --> 00:15:01,400
But I got big ideas.

161
00:15:02,152 --> 00:15:03,702
I'm sure you do.

162
00:15:03,904 --> 00:15:07,744
For instance,
take a look at this sweet baby.

163
00:15:11,620 --> 00:15:12,960
I developed it myself.

164
00:15:13,163 --> 00:15:15,793
Yes, sirree, this is my ticket upstairs.

165
00:15:19,169 --> 00:15:20,959
You know, for kids.

166
00:15:21,672 --> 00:15:23,262
Terrific.

167
00:15:23,757 --> 00:15:26,467
So you see, I won't be working
in the mail room long.

168
00:15:26,677 --> 00:15:29,757
No, I don't guess you will be.

169
00:15:29,972 --> 00:15:32,932
- How long you been here?
- Forty-eight years.

170
00:15:33,434 --> 00:15:37,814
Next year they move me up to parcels
if I'm lucky.

171
00:15:38,022 --> 00:15:40,112
<i>MAN [ON PA]:
Attention Hudsucker employees!</i>

172
00:15:40,316 --> 00:15:42,476
<i>Attention Hudsucker employees!</i>

173
00:15:42,693 --> 00:15:46,413
<i>We regretfully announce
that at 30 seconds after the hour of noon...</i>

174
00:15:46,614 --> 00:15:47,704
<i>...Hudsucker time...</i>

175
00:15:47,907 --> 00:15:50,657
<i>Waring Hudsucker,
founder, president...</i>

176
00:15:50,868 --> 00:15:53,658
<i>...and chairman of the
board of Hudsucker Industries...</i>

177
00:15:53,871 --> 00:15:55,211
<i>...merged with the infinite.</i>

178
00:15:55,414 --> 00:15:58,384
<i>To mark this occasion of corporate loss...</i>

179
00:15:58,584 --> 00:16:03,134
<i>...we ask that all employees observe
a moment of silent contemplation.</i>

180
00:16:07,301 --> 00:16:08,471
[EMPLOYEE COUGHS]

181
00:16:09,428 --> 00:16:11,468
<i>MAN [ON PA]:
Thank you for your kind attention.</i>

182
00:16:11,680 --> 00:16:14,520
<i>This moment has been duly noted
on your timecards...</i>

183
00:16:14,725 --> 00:16:18,185
<i>...and will be deducted from your pay.
That is all.</i>

184
00:16:18,395 --> 00:16:19,805
[ALARMS WAILING]

185
00:16:21,315 --> 00:16:23,855
- Blue letter!
- Blue letter!

186
00:16:24,068 --> 00:16:25,778
They're bringing down a blue letter!

187
00:16:59,895 --> 00:17:01,475
OLD MAN:
It's a blue letter.

188
00:17:02,064 --> 00:17:03,864
TOP, top level.

189
00:17:04,066 --> 00:17:06,736
Confidential communication
between the brass.

190
00:17:07,403 --> 00:17:09,573
Usually bad news.

191
00:17:09,780 --> 00:17:11,910
They hate blue letters upstairs.

192
00:17:15,828 --> 00:17:18,118
- Hate them.
- You!

193
00:17:18,330 --> 00:17:21,460
Yeah, you! Barnes!
You don't look busy!

194
00:17:22,126 --> 00:17:24,336
Think you can handle a blue letter?

195
00:17:24,545 --> 00:17:27,205
This letter was sent this morning
by the big man himself...

196
00:17:27,423 --> 00:17:29,013
...that's right, Waring Hudsucker!

197
00:17:29,216 --> 00:17:32,756
It's addressed to Sid Mussburger,
Hudsucker's right-hand man!

198
00:17:32,970 --> 00:17:34,510
It's a blue letter!

199
00:17:34,888 --> 00:17:37,928
That means you got to put it
right in Mussburger's hands.

200
00:17:38,142 --> 00:17:40,352
No secretaries! No receptionists!

201
00:17:40,561 --> 00:17:43,521
No colleagues! No excuses!

202
00:17:43,731 --> 00:17:45,231
Mussburger!

203
00:17:46,817 --> 00:17:51,107
Hi, my name's Buzz, I got the fuzz,
I make the elevator do what she does.

204
00:17:51,780 --> 00:17:54,320
Hang it up to dry.
What's your pleasure, buddy?

205
00:17:54,533 --> 00:17:57,243
- Forty-four.
- Forty-four, the top-brass floor.

206
00:17:57,453 --> 00:18:00,213
Say, buddy, what takes
50 years to get to the top floor...

207
00:18:00,414 --> 00:18:02,174
...and 30 seconds to get down?

208
00:18:02,374 --> 00:18:04,714
Waring Hudsucker! You get it, buddy?

209
00:18:04,918 --> 00:18:08,418
Say, buddy! Mr. Kline, up to nine.
Mrs. Dell, Personnel.

210
00:18:08,630 --> 00:18:10,300
- Mr. Levin, 37.
- Thirty-six.

211
00:18:10,507 --> 00:18:13,177
Walk down! Ladies and gentlemen,
please step to the rear.

212
00:18:13,385 --> 00:18:16,635
- Here comes the gargantuan Mr. Grier.
- Buzz.

213
00:18:17,848 --> 00:18:20,768
Say, buddy, who's the most liquid
businessman on the street?

214
00:18:21,351 --> 00:18:23,231
Waring Hudsucker. Say, buddy.

215
00:18:23,437 --> 00:18:27,477
When is the sidewalk fully dressed?
When it's wearing Hudsucker! Ha-ha-ha.

216
00:18:28,317 --> 00:18:30,687
You get it, buddy?
It's a pun, it's a knee-slapper...

217
00:18:30,903 --> 00:18:34,163
...it's a play on-- Jesus, Joseph and Mary,
is that a blue letter?

218
00:18:34,364 --> 00:18:39,454
Why didn't you tell a guy? Hold on, folks,
we're express to the top floor!

219
00:18:39,661 --> 00:18:40,871
[ELEVATOR WHIRRING]

220
00:18:41,747 --> 00:18:43,207
[ELEVATOR BELL DINGS]

221
00:18:54,051 --> 00:18:55,761
Good luck, buddy.

222
00:18:58,639 --> 00:19:00,679
You're gonna need it. Ha-ha-ha.

223
00:19:01,058 --> 00:19:03,018
[SCRAPING]

224
00:19:11,735 --> 00:19:12,685
[CLEARS THROAT]

225
00:19:12,903 --> 00:19:14,493
Mr. Mussburger's office?

226
00:20:10,043 --> 00:20:11,633
[CLEARS THROAT]

227
00:20:12,462 --> 00:20:13,762
[IN SOFT VOICE]
Hello.

228
00:20:13,964 --> 00:20:17,724
- Do you have an appointment?
- No.

229
00:20:17,926 --> 00:20:22,006
- Shall we look in the book? Hmm?
- Ma'am, we shall--

230
00:20:22,222 --> 00:20:25,272
- We don't seem to be in the book.
- I wouldn't be.

231
00:20:25,475 --> 00:20:29,435
If we had an appointment,
we'd be in the book.

232
00:20:29,646 --> 00:20:31,186
[PANTING]
I have this, uh...

233
00:20:31,398 --> 00:20:32,518
Oh, here it is. Heh.

234
00:20:33,483 --> 00:20:35,283
[SCREAMING]

235
00:20:38,197 --> 00:20:39,907
MUSSBURGER:
Gambotz?

236
00:20:40,115 --> 00:20:41,445
Harry Gambotz?

237
00:20:41,658 --> 00:20:45,038
No, too risky.
He's green but he's not slow.

238
00:20:45,787 --> 00:20:46,957
Who is he?

239
00:20:47,164 --> 00:20:50,004
No, I want an imbecile, not a cipher
or you'd have the job.

240
00:20:51,168 --> 00:20:52,168
Nuh-nuh.

241
00:20:52,377 --> 00:20:54,457
They moved him to grommets
and O-rings.

242
00:20:54,671 --> 00:20:56,131
He's doing pretty well.

243
00:20:57,090 --> 00:20:59,640
No, no, not, McClanahan.

244
00:20:59,843 --> 00:21:02,893
He bungled the Teleyard merger,
thinks he's got something to prove.

245
00:21:03,096 --> 00:21:04,846
Who let you in?

246
00:21:05,057 --> 00:21:08,637
Atwater? Tremendous.
Except I just fired him last week.

247
00:21:08,852 --> 00:21:10,232
WOMAN [OVER INTERCOM]:
<i>Mr. Mussburger...</i>

248
00:21:10,437 --> 00:21:11,897
<i>...Mr. Bumstead's waiting downstairs.</i>

249
00:21:12,105 --> 00:21:14,185
- I'll be right there.
WOMAN: Yes, Mr. Mussburger.

250
00:21:14,399 --> 00:21:15,479
Spit it out!

251
00:21:15,692 --> 00:21:17,572
- I, uh...
- Yeah?

252
00:21:17,778 --> 00:21:20,198
Well, maybe you're
the company's biggest moron.

253
00:21:20,405 --> 00:21:24,025
We can't use Morris. Been here too long.
He's a nice guy with too many friends.

254
00:21:24,243 --> 00:21:27,503
In fact, why don't you fire him?
Scratch that, I'll fire him.

255
00:21:27,704 --> 00:21:29,464
Make it fast, huh, fast!

256
00:21:29,665 --> 00:21:31,535
<i>WOMAN [OVER INTERCOM]:
Mr. Bumstead is growing restless.</i>

257
00:21:31,750 --> 00:21:33,920
MUSSBURGER: Tell him I'll be right there.
Give him a magazine.

258
00:21:34,127 --> 00:21:35,547
What, are you a mute?

259
00:21:35,754 --> 00:21:37,174
[PHONE RINGS]

260
00:21:37,506 --> 00:21:39,546
How's the stock doing? Bad?

261
00:21:39,758 --> 00:21:42,678
Well, it's not bad enough.
Listen, chump.

262
00:21:42,886 --> 00:21:46,926
Either you find me a ding-dong or tender
your key to the executive washroom.

263
00:21:47,140 --> 00:21:50,690
That goes double for you, pal.
Ear-clay? Ood-gay!

264
00:21:54,898 --> 00:21:57,528
This better be good. I'm in a bad mood.

265
00:21:58,485 --> 00:22:01,775
Sir, I've got something for you
from the mail room, but first...

266
00:22:01,989 --> 00:22:06,949
...if I could take a minute of your very
valuable time to show you something...

267
00:22:07,160 --> 00:22:10,330
...I've been working on
for the past two or three years.

268
00:22:11,081 --> 00:22:12,751
[METAL BALLS STRIKING]

269
00:22:17,379 --> 00:22:18,709
You know, for kids.

270
00:22:19,715 --> 00:22:22,625
It's perfect for Hudsucker,
not that I'm any great genius.

271
00:22:22,843 --> 00:22:25,053
They say inspiration
is 99 percent perspiration...

272
00:22:25,262 --> 00:22:27,142
...in my case
it's at least twice that...

273
00:22:27,347 --> 00:22:30,057
...but I've got to tell you, this sweet--
- Wait a minute!

274
00:22:38,400 --> 00:22:39,780
Huh.

275
00:22:56,460 --> 00:22:57,920
Hmm.

276
00:23:14,644 --> 00:23:16,364
Sit down, son.

277
00:23:18,648 --> 00:23:20,108
Go ahead.

278
00:23:21,693 --> 00:23:23,243
Try it on.

279
00:23:36,333 --> 00:23:37,293
Put your feet up.

280
00:23:41,463 --> 00:23:42,553
Go ahead.

281
00:23:44,758 --> 00:23:48,138
Let's get to know one another, shall we?

282
00:23:49,012 --> 00:23:50,642
Let's chat.

283
00:23:53,600 --> 00:23:54,600
Man-to-man.

284
00:23:58,480 --> 00:24:04,240
Now then,
you're from the basement, aren't you?

285
00:24:05,445 --> 00:24:08,365
And weren't blessed with much...

286
00:24:09,699 --> 00:24:10,989
...education?

287
00:24:11,368 --> 00:24:13,998
Well, I am a college graduate.

288
00:24:14,204 --> 00:24:16,624
But you did not excel in your studies.

289
00:24:16,832 --> 00:24:19,502
- Well, I... I made Dean's List.
- Oh.

290
00:24:19,709 --> 00:24:21,919
At the Muncie College
of Business Administration.

291
00:24:22,129 --> 00:24:23,509
[CHUCKLES]

292
00:24:23,713 --> 00:24:26,803
And your friends, they called you "jerk,"
didn't they?

293
00:24:27,008 --> 00:24:28,048
Mm, unh-uhn.

294
00:24:28,260 --> 00:24:30,140
- "Dope?" "Dipstick?"
- Mm-mm. No.

295
00:24:30,345 --> 00:24:32,845
"Lamebrain?" "Schmo?"
Not even behind your back?

296
00:24:33,056 --> 00:24:35,846
Well, as a matter they voted me
"Most Likely to Succeed."

297
00:24:36,059 --> 00:24:37,309
You're fired.

298
00:24:37,519 --> 00:24:39,059
[BOTH GRUNTING]

299
00:24:39,271 --> 00:24:43,021
Get your feet off my desk,
get out of my office.

300
00:24:43,233 --> 00:24:45,153
Leave your apron in the locker room.

301
00:24:45,360 --> 00:24:46,360
Oh! my God!"

302
00:24:46,570 --> 00:24:50,950
The Bumstead contract. I've been
working on that deal for four years!

303
00:24:51,158 --> 00:24:53,198
Get out of here!
I'll take care of it! Get out.

304
00:24:54,035 --> 00:24:57,115
You could have destroyed
the most sensitive document of my career.

305
00:24:57,330 --> 00:24:59,750
<i>WOMAN: Mr. Bumstead
is threatening to leave the building.</i>

306
00:24:59,958 --> 00:25:01,078
I'm on my way down.

307
00:25:01,293 --> 00:25:03,883
We need the first page
of the contract retyped.

308
00:25:04,087 --> 00:25:05,047
[PHONE RINGS]

309
00:25:05,255 --> 00:25:06,715
WOMAN :
<i>Yes, Mr. Mussburger.</i>

310
00:25:06,923 --> 00:25:10,143
Yeah? Uh-huh. Yeah.

311
00:25:10,343 --> 00:25:11,973
Out! Out of the office!

312
00:25:14,681 --> 00:25:15,971
Down three points, huh?

313
00:25:16,183 --> 00:25:18,523
That's encouraging.
How about New York?

314
00:25:19,436 --> 00:25:21,516
Not that way, through the door!

315
00:25:21,730 --> 00:25:24,230
<i>WOMAN: Sir, it'll take three hours
to retype the Bumstead contract...</i>

316
00:25:25,108 --> 00:25:28,028
MUSSBURGER: Where are you going?
Get out of here! Stop that!

317
00:25:28,236 --> 00:25:29,946
WOMAN:
<i>Mr. Bumstead's threatening to leave.</i>

318
00:25:30,155 --> 00:25:31,235
Not the whole contract,
just the first page.

319
00:25:31,448 --> 00:25:32,408
[NORVILLE MUMBLING]

320
00:25:32,616 --> 00:25:34,486
I'll be there.
Give him another magazine.

321
00:25:34,701 --> 00:25:36,701
<i>WOMAN: He says he'll leave.
MUSSBURGER: I said I'll be there!</i>

322
00:25:36,912 --> 00:25:38,912
<i>And you're wife's been trying to reach you.</i>

323
00:25:39,122 --> 00:25:42,332
Up on your feet! We don't crawl
here at Hudsucker Industries!

324
00:25:42,542 --> 00:25:44,132
- My leg is on fire!
- No assumptions!

325
00:25:44,336 --> 00:25:48,586
It's early yet. Just let me know
where we stand at the closing bell.

326
00:25:48,798 --> 00:25:50,508
[PHONE RINGING]

327
00:25:53,595 --> 00:25:54,845
[GRUNTS]

328
00:25:57,432 --> 00:25:59,772
Oh, my God, the Bumstead contract!

329
00:25:59,976 --> 00:26:02,226
[NORVILLE MUMBLING]

330
00:26:05,315 --> 00:26:07,145
No magazines! No coffee!

331
00:26:07,359 --> 00:26:12,279
Mussburger! I wanna see Mussburger!
Or did he jump out a window too?

332
00:26:12,948 --> 00:26:16,578
Don't worry, Mr. Mussburger, I got you!
I got you by your pants.

333
00:26:19,579 --> 00:26:21,329
Pants?

334
00:26:25,001 --> 00:26:28,841
Mr. Mussburger, I'm gonna
give your pants a nice double stitch.

335
00:26:29,047 --> 00:26:33,927
It'll make them real strong
and you're gonna look real sharp.

336
00:26:34,135 --> 00:26:39,265
- No, single stitch is fine.
- But the double stitch, she lasts forever.

337
00:26:40,267 --> 00:26:43,897
Why on earth would I want
a double stitch?

338
00:26:44,104 --> 00:26:45,814
To pad your account.

339
00:26:46,022 --> 00:26:47,822
Single stitch is fine.

340
00:26:53,905 --> 00:26:55,445
Damn!

341
00:26:57,826 --> 00:27:01,116
[HUMMING]

342
00:27:01,329 --> 00:27:05,209
Oh, what the heck!
Mr. Mussburger is such a nice man...

343
00:27:05,417 --> 00:27:08,547
...I'm gonna give him
a double stitch anyway. Heh-heh-heh.

344
00:27:09,087 --> 00:27:12,797
Ah. That's some strong stitch, you bet!

345
00:27:23,560 --> 00:27:25,940
[ALL LAUGHING]

346
00:27:39,909 --> 00:27:41,869
[NORVILLE LAUGHING]

347
00:27:51,046 --> 00:27:53,006
[CONTINUES LAUGHING]

348
00:27:57,260 --> 00:27:59,220
[GROUP LAUGHING]

349
00:28:20,909 --> 00:28:22,869
[LAUGHING]

350
00:28:31,670 --> 00:28:33,630
[LAUGHING]

351
00:28:58,738 --> 00:29:01,738
AL:
"The Einstein of Enterprise."

352
00:29:01,950 --> 00:29:04,330
"The Edison of Industry."

353
00:29:04,703 --> 00:29:07,583
"The Billion-Dollar Cranium!"

354
00:29:08,832 --> 00:29:11,172
"Idea Man!"

355
00:29:12,210 --> 00:29:14,550
And not one of you has given me
a story on him!

356
00:29:14,754 --> 00:29:16,594
Bunch of lamebrains!

357
00:29:16,798 --> 00:29:19,128
Facts, figures, charts.
They never sold a newspaper!

358
00:29:19,342 --> 00:29:21,932
I read this morning's Argus,
let me tell you something.

359
00:29:22,137 --> 00:29:24,807
I'd wrap a fish in it!
I'd use it as kindling!

360
00:29:25,014 --> 00:29:27,604
I'd train my poodle on it
if he wasn't a French poodle...

361
00:29:27,809 --> 00:29:29,519
...and partial to pages of Paris-Soir.

362
00:29:29,728 --> 00:29:32,648
But I wouldn't shell out a hard-earned
nickel to read the thing!

363
00:29:32,856 --> 00:29:34,766
Come on, chief, give us a break.

364
00:29:34,983 --> 00:29:37,823
Sure, Tibbs. Take a break.

365
00:29:38,027 --> 00:29:40,567
Go to Florida. Lie in the sun.

366
00:29:40,780 --> 00:29:43,370
Wait for a coconut to drop.
File a story on it.

367
00:29:43,575 --> 00:29:46,785
It'd be more of a grabber than your piece
on the county grain surplus!

368
00:29:46,995 --> 00:29:49,655
The human angle!
That's what sells papers!

369
00:29:49,873 --> 00:29:53,173
We need a front page with a heart
and the Idea Man can put it there!

370
00:29:53,376 --> 00:29:54,996
Look, chief, if we had more access--

371
00:29:55,211 --> 00:29:57,761
If a frog had wings
it wouldn't bump it's ass a-hopping.

372
00:29:57,964 --> 00:29:59,764
I don't want excuses, I want results!

373
00:29:59,966 --> 00:30:02,506
What makes the Idea Man tick?
Where's he from?

374
00:30:02,719 --> 00:30:06,349
I want to know everything about him!
Has he got a girl? Has he got parents?

375
00:30:06,556 --> 00:30:08,596
Everybody has parents.

376
00:30:08,808 --> 00:30:10,848
All right, how many?

377
00:30:11,394 --> 00:30:14,524
How about it, Parkinson?
You've been awful quiet over there.

378
00:30:14,731 --> 00:30:16,861
- Uh...
- Still waters run deep.

379
00:30:17,066 --> 00:30:19,686
Only thing deep with Parkinson
are the holes in his ears.

380
00:30:19,903 --> 00:30:21,743
Yes, Idea Man.

381
00:30:21,946 --> 00:30:25,366
What are his hopes and dreams,
his desires and aspirations?

382
00:30:25,575 --> 00:30:28,195
Does he think all the time
or a certain portion of the day?

383
00:30:28,411 --> 00:30:30,581
How tall is he? Shoe size?
Where does he sleep?

384
00:30:30,789 --> 00:30:32,209
What does he have for breakfast?

385
00:30:32,415 --> 00:30:34,285
Does he put jam on his toast
or doesn't he?

386
00:30:34,501 --> 00:30:36,541
If not, why not and since when?

387
00:30:37,295 --> 00:30:38,705
Well?

388
00:30:39,672 --> 00:30:41,722
Ah. You're useless.

389
00:30:41,925 --> 00:30:44,715
Yes. Idea Man. "Creator."

390
00:30:44,928 --> 00:30:47,968
"Innovator." "Cerebrator."

391
00:30:48,181 --> 00:30:49,891
WOMAN: Fake!
- Huh?

392
00:30:50,099 --> 00:30:51,809
I tell you, the guy's a phony-

393
00:30:52,018 --> 00:30:53,558
AL: Phony, huh?
- As a three-dollar bill.

394
00:30:53,770 --> 00:30:55,190
- Says who?
- Says me, Amy Archer!

395
00:30:55,396 --> 00:30:57,726
Why is he an Idea Man?
Because Hudsucker says he is?

396
00:30:57,941 --> 00:31:00,571
What are his ideas?
Why can't anyone interview him?

397
00:31:00,777 --> 00:31:03,397
Five bucks says
she mentions her Pulitzer.

398
00:31:03,613 --> 00:31:05,573
Again? You're on.

399
00:31:05,782 --> 00:31:07,832
Just take a look at the mug on this guy.

400
00:31:08,034 --> 00:31:10,794
The jutting eyebrows, the simian forehead,
the idiotic grin.

401
00:31:10,995 --> 00:31:15,285
He has a face only a mother could love
on payday.

402
00:31:15,500 --> 00:31:18,090
The only story here is how
this guy made a monkey out of you, Al.

403
00:31:18,294 --> 00:31:19,254
[GIBBERS]

404
00:31:19,462 --> 00:31:21,012
Yeah, monkey or not,
I'm still editor of this rag.

405
00:31:21,214 --> 00:31:24,224
You were doing the piece on the FBI.
"Hoover: When Will He Marry?"

406
00:31:24,425 --> 00:31:27,425
- I filed it yesterday. Nice tie, Earl.
- Well, do a follow-up.

407
00:31:27,637 --> 00:31:29,557
"Hoover: Crime Buster or Pantywaist?"

408
00:31:29,764 --> 00:31:33,274
The rest of you mugs get off your brains
and get me that Idea Man story!

409
00:31:33,476 --> 00:31:36,186
Al, he's the bunk.

410
00:31:41,985 --> 00:31:44,445
- I'll stake my Pulitzer on it!
MAN: Hmm.

411
00:31:46,322 --> 00:31:48,282
Say, buddy,
where'd you get the new duds?

412
00:31:48,491 --> 00:31:51,791
Say, buddy, how did old bucket butt
like his blue letter? Heh.

413
00:31:51,995 --> 00:31:55,325
Did he bust a gut? Did he die?
Well, hello, Mr. Mussburger.

414
00:31:55,540 --> 00:31:58,250
- Lobby, we haven't got all day.
- Right away, Mr. Mussburger.

415
00:31:58,751 --> 00:32:00,591
How are you this fine morning, sir?

416
00:32:01,254 --> 00:32:03,724
It's been a pleasure serving you today,
sir.

417
00:32:03,923 --> 00:32:06,763
It's been a pleasure serving you too, uh,
buddy.

418
00:32:06,968 --> 00:32:09,008
Uh, Sid, shouldn't we be
a little concerned...

419
00:32:09,220 --> 00:32:11,970
...with the downward spiral of our stock
these past few clays?

420
00:32:12,181 --> 00:32:14,481
You're the expert,
but at the Muncie College...

421
00:32:14,684 --> 00:32:16,444
Relax, it's only natural...

422
00:32:16,644 --> 00:32:19,984
...in a period of transition for the more
timid element to run for cover.

423
00:32:20,189 --> 00:32:21,649
Like I said, you're the expert...

424
00:32:21,858 --> 00:32:24,278
...but do you remember the plan
I outlined for you...

425
00:32:24,485 --> 00:32:27,315
...the day I set fire to your office?
The clay I was promoted?

426
00:32:27,530 --> 00:32:32,790
I do remember and I was impressed.
But that's all forgotten now.

427
00:32:33,953 --> 00:32:35,373
NORVILLE:
Oh. Thank you, Sid.

428
00:32:35,997 --> 00:32:39,327
The reason I mention it is it requires
such a small capital investment--

429
00:32:39,542 --> 00:32:41,002
Again, you are the expert here.

430
00:32:41,210 --> 00:32:43,420
- -But there's such an enormous
potential profit...

431
00:32:43,630 --> 00:32:46,630
...given the discretionary income
of the burgeoning middle-class.

432
00:32:46,841 --> 00:32:47,841
[TIRES SCREECH]

433
00:32:48,051 --> 00:32:50,141
So if you agree, I'd like to bounce the idea
off a few people at lunch.

434
00:32:50,345 --> 00:32:51,505
Sure, sure.

435
00:32:51,721 --> 00:32:55,351
Tell whoever you want.
I'd like to hear about it at some point too.

436
00:33:04,609 --> 00:33:09,199
- I got gas, Benny.
- Yeah. Tell me about it.

437
00:33:09,405 --> 00:33:12,365
LOU:
No kidding, Benny. I got gas.

438
00:33:12,575 --> 00:33:15,905
BENNY: You get the special?
LOU: Far from it.

439
00:33:17,789 --> 00:33:19,249
[LOU WHISTLES]

440
00:33:19,457 --> 00:33:21,167
LOU:
Enter the dame.

441
00:33:21,376 --> 00:33:23,836
BENNY:
There's one in every story.

442
00:33:24,045 --> 00:33:26,705
LOU: Ten bucks says
she's looking for a handout.

443
00:33:26,923 --> 00:33:30,263
BENNY: Twenty bucks says not here,
she don't find one.

444
00:33:30,468 --> 00:33:33,218
LOU: She's looking for her mark.
BENNY: She finds him.

445
00:33:33,429 --> 00:33:38,559
LOU: She sits down
and orders a light lunch.

446
00:33:39,268 --> 00:33:41,808
BENNY:
How will she pay for this lunch?

447
00:33:42,021 --> 00:33:45,441
LOU: She looks through her purse.
BENNY: No money.

448
00:33:45,650 --> 00:33:48,150
LOU:
The mark notices.

449
00:33:48,778 --> 00:33:52,068
- He's not noticing, Benny.
BENNY: Maybe he's wise.

450
00:33:52,281 --> 00:33:54,701
LOU:
He don't look wise.

451
00:33:55,994 --> 00:33:57,334
BENNY:
Plan two.

452
00:33:57,537 --> 00:33:59,457
Here come the waterworks.

453
00:33:59,664 --> 00:34:01,714
LOU: Yellowstone.
BENNY: Old Faithful.

454
00:34:01,916 --> 00:34:03,876
LOU:
Hello, Niagara.

455
00:34:04,085 --> 00:34:06,835
BENNY: He notices.
LOU: She's distressed.

456
00:34:07,046 --> 00:34:08,836
BENNY:
He's concerned.

457
00:34:09,048 --> 00:34:11,218
LOU:
She explains her predicament.

458
00:34:11,426 --> 00:34:16,006
LOU AND BENNY [IN UNISON]:
And enter the light lunch.

459
00:34:16,222 --> 00:34:20,602
BENNY: She's got other problems.
LOU: There's illness in the family.

460
00:34:20,810 --> 00:34:23,600
BENNY: Her mother needs an operation.
LOU: Urgently.

461
00:34:23,813 --> 00:34:26,573
BENNY: Adenoids.
LOU: No, Benny.

462
00:34:27,025 --> 00:34:29,145
Lumbago.

463
00:34:29,360 --> 00:34:31,530
BENNY:
That gag's got whiskers on it.

464
00:34:31,738 --> 00:34:34,408
LOU:
Uh-oh. He ain't biting, Benny.

465
00:34:34,615 --> 00:34:37,615
BENNY: She's losing him, Lou.
LOU: Maybe he's wise.

466
00:34:37,827 --> 00:34:39,947
BENNY:
He don't look wise.

467
00:34:40,163 --> 00:34:42,793
LOU: How does she pull this out?
BENNY: He's getting away.

468
00:34:42,999 --> 00:34:46,419
LOU: She better think fast.
BENNY: She isn't.

469
00:34:46,627 --> 00:34:48,757
LOU AND BENNY [IN UNISON]:
She is!

470
00:34:48,963 --> 00:34:50,803
LOU:
She's good, Benny.

471
00:34:51,007 --> 00:34:53,127
BENNY:
She's damn good, Lou.

472
00:34:53,843 --> 00:34:56,103
Can I get you boys anything else?

473
00:34:58,181 --> 00:34:59,771
Bromo.

474
00:35:00,183 --> 00:35:01,773
Bromo.

475
00:35:03,478 --> 00:35:06,978
AMY: I'm sorry we had to take the stairs.
It was just that horrible elevator boy.

476
00:35:07,190 --> 00:35:10,110
I can't say how much I appreciate
your listening to my story.

477
00:35:10,318 --> 00:35:14,318
I'm lucky to find someone in this bustling
city with a stout heart and a ready ear.

478
00:35:14,530 --> 00:35:17,450
At any rate, there I was traveling
this great country.

479
00:35:17,658 --> 00:35:18,788
Some I met were kind to me,
others exceedingly cruel.

480
00:35:18,993 --> 00:35:20,043
[NORVILLE PANTING]

481
00:35:20,244 --> 00:35:22,464
Traveling by motor bus, rail,
even by thumb.

482
00:35:22,663 --> 00:35:23,963
The couch, please.

483
00:35:24,165 --> 00:35:27,585
Hoarding every dollar, counting
every nickel, pinching every penny.

484
00:35:27,794 --> 00:35:30,514
It's been a long road leading
to the coffee shop downstairs.

485
00:35:30,713 --> 00:35:34,093
Not that I'd trade a day, an hour,
a moment of it for anything.

486
00:35:34,300 --> 00:35:35,720
I don't know what came over me.

487
00:35:35,927 --> 00:35:37,847
It was the shock of eating
after so long...

488
00:35:38,054 --> 00:35:40,934
...without the enzymes kicking in
after so long...

489
00:35:41,140 --> 00:35:44,770
[MUTED DIALOGUE]

490
00:35:45,144 --> 00:35:48,194
Then you couldn't possibly know
what it is to be tired and hungry.

491
00:35:48,397 --> 00:35:50,317
- Hungry, anyway.
- I don't wanna bore you...

492
00:35:50,525 --> 00:35:52,735
...with all details of my life.
Not a happy story.

493
00:35:52,944 --> 00:35:55,244
I'm jobless
but not for want of trying.

494
00:35:55,446 --> 00:35:58,906
I'm friendless, with no one to take care
of me and had you not come along...

495
00:35:59,117 --> 00:36:01,327
...exactly when you did...
NORVILLE: I, myself--

496
00:36:01,536 --> 00:36:03,786
At any rate, I arrived in town
not 10 days ago...

497
00:36:03,996 --> 00:36:07,326
...full of dreams and aspirations,
anxious to make my way in the world...

498
00:36:07,542 --> 00:36:08,792
...a little naive perhaps...

499
00:36:09,001 --> 00:36:11,051
...but armed with determination,
work ethic...

500
00:36:11,254 --> 00:36:12,714
...and a belief in the future...

501
00:36:12,922 --> 00:36:14,882
- I, myself--
AMY: ...only to have that belief...

502
00:36:15,091 --> 00:36:18,341
...that unsullied optimism, dashed against
the marble of the workplace.

503
00:36:18,553 --> 00:36:21,563
Such is life. Seek and you shall
find. Work and you shall prosper.

504
00:36:21,764 --> 00:36:23,224
- Cigarette?
- No, thank you.

505
00:36:23,432 --> 00:36:25,812
Seek and you shall find,
work and you shall prosper.

506
00:36:26,018 --> 00:36:28,228
These were the watchwords
of my education...

507
00:36:28,437 --> 00:36:30,187
...the values instilled in me...

508
00:36:30,398 --> 00:36:33,528
...while I was growing up in a little town
you've never heard of.

509
00:36:33,734 --> 00:36:35,244
- Mind if I join you?
- Be my guest.

510
00:36:35,444 --> 00:36:37,534
A little town you've probably
never heard of...

511
00:36:37,738 --> 00:36:39,528
...a dusty crossroads of which
you've probably never heard.

512
00:36:39,740 --> 00:36:40,740
[SCREAMS]

513
00:36:41,951 --> 00:36:45,121
Excuse me. Executive washroom.

514
00:36:45,830 --> 00:36:47,460
[NORVILLE GROANING]

515
00:36:47,665 --> 00:36:49,415
Are you all right?

516
00:36:49,625 --> 00:36:51,085
[NORVILLE YELLING]

517
00:36:51,294 --> 00:36:54,464
Is it your lunch?
The chicken a': la king?

518
00:36:56,591 --> 00:37:01,641
- Is the à la king repeating on you?
- No, I'm fine. You were saying?

519
00:37:03,347 --> 00:37:04,467
Uh...

520
00:37:04,682 --> 00:37:06,932
[IN LOW VOICE]
Values, watchwords, tender years.

521
00:37:07,143 --> 00:37:10,773
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
A town you've probably never heard of.

522
00:37:10,980 --> 00:37:13,440
Muncie, Indiana.

523
00:37:13,649 --> 00:37:18,859
- You're from Muncie?
- Why, yes. Do you know it?

524
00:37:20,531 --> 00:37:24,291
Uh... Uhn!

525
00:37:24,660 --> 00:37:26,660
[NORVILLE YELLING AND GRUNTING]

526
00:37:36,088 --> 00:37:37,798
[SINGING]
<i>Fight</i> on

527
00:37:38,007 --> 00:37:41,297
<i>Fight on
Dear old Muncie</i>

528
00:37:41,510 --> 00:37:42,800
<i>Fight on</i>

529
00:37:43,012 --> 00:37:45,472
<i>Hoist the gold and blue</i>

530
00:37:45,681 --> 00:37:49,481
<i>You'll be tattered
Torn and hurting</i>

531
00:37:49,685 --> 00:37:54,315
<i>Once the Muncie's done with</i>

532
00:37:54,523 --> 00:37:57,783
<i>You</i>

533
00:37:57,985 --> 00:38:00,905
<i>You</i>

534
00:38:01,113 --> 00:38:06,583
"Go, Eagles!
"Go, Eagles!

535
00:38:06,786 --> 00:38:09,206
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

536
00:38:10,748 --> 00:38:11,788
A Muncie girl!

537
00:38:11,958 --> 00:38:13,748
- What do you know about that?
- Hmm.

538
00:38:14,877 --> 00:38:15,917
I'll tell you what, Amy.

539
00:38:16,128 --> 00:38:18,208
I'm gonna cancel the rest
of my appointments...

540
00:38:18,422 --> 00:38:19,972
...and get you a job here at Hud.

541
00:38:20,174 --> 00:38:21,844
Oh, no! Really--

542
00:38:22,051 --> 00:38:25,391
Don't bother to thank me. It's easy.
I know where a vacancy just came up.

543
00:38:25,596 --> 00:38:27,846
- Mailroom. This will only take a moment.
MAN [OVER INTERCOM]: Yeah.

544
00:38:28,057 --> 00:38:29,847
Good afternoon, this is Norville Barnes.

545
00:38:30,059 --> 00:38:31,689
<i>MUSSBURGER [OVER INTERCOM]:
Barnes! Where the hell have you been?</i>

546
00:38:31,894 --> 00:38:34,984
<i>- Where's my voucher?
- Umh!</i>

547
00:38:35,189 --> 00:38:36,859
<i>- I'm not sure.
- I need that voucher!</i>

548
00:38:37,066 --> 00:38:39,186
<i>I told you a week ago it was important!</i>

549
00:38:40,069 --> 00:38:42,069
Ahem, I'm president of the company now.

550
00:38:42,280 --> 00:38:45,660
<i>I don't care
if you're president of the company!</i>

551
00:38:45,866 --> 00:38:47,866
<i>I need the voucher now!</i>

552
00:38:49,328 --> 00:38:51,538
Look, why don't you work in here
with me?

553
00:38:51,747 --> 00:38:53,917
Are you familiar
with the mimeograph machine?

554
00:38:54,083 --> 00:38:59,013
Well, of course. I went to the
Muncie Secretarial, uh, Polytechnic.

555
00:38:59,213 --> 00:39:01,053
A Muncie girl! Can you beat that?

556
00:39:01,966 --> 00:39:04,546
I just don't know
how to thank you, Mr. Barnes.

557
00:39:04,760 --> 00:39:06,550
Please, Norville.

558
00:39:06,762 --> 00:39:10,642
NORVILLE: Go, Eagles! Heh.
AMY: Go, Eagles!

559
00:39:10,850 --> 00:39:13,140
[SMITTY LAUGHING]

560
00:39:13,769 --> 00:39:16,939
"Once the Munce..." Holy moly!

561
00:39:17,148 --> 00:39:20,398
Is this guy from Chumpsville?
I even pulled the old mother routine.

562
00:39:20,609 --> 00:39:21,779
- Adenoids?
- Lumbago.

563
00:39:22,278 --> 00:39:24,108
Phew. That gag's got whiskers on it.

564
00:39:24,322 --> 00:39:25,412
AMY: I tell you,
the Hudsucker board's up to something.

565
00:39:25,614 --> 00:39:26,704
[PHONE RINGING]

566
00:39:26,907 --> 00:39:29,787
What's a six-letter word
for an affliction of the hypothalamus?

567
00:39:29,994 --> 00:39:32,464
And it's a cinch-- Goiter.
- -this guy isn't in on it.

568
00:39:32,663 --> 00:39:35,293
SMITTY: She's right here.
- How much time to make the late final?

569
00:39:35,499 --> 00:39:37,789
- Chief.
- Tsk. Hiya, chief.

570
00:39:38,002 --> 00:39:39,882
Just the person I wanted to apologize to.

571
00:39:40,087 --> 00:39:43,757
- About seven minutes.
- Yeah, I was all wet about your Idea Man.

572
00:39:43,966 --> 00:39:48,716
Well, thanks for being so generous.
It is human and you are divine.

573
00:39:48,929 --> 00:39:51,269
No, he's no faker.

574
00:39:51,474 --> 00:39:54,774
He's 100 percent real McCoy,
beware of imitations, genuine article.

575
00:39:54,977 --> 00:39:58,357
The guy's a real moron,
as in a five-letter word for imbecile.

576
00:39:58,564 --> 00:40:01,694
Oh, as pure a specimen
as I've ever run across. Okay.

577
00:40:01,901 --> 00:40:04,281
If working at the <i>Argus</i>
doesn't make me an expert...

578
00:40:04,487 --> 00:40:07,987
...then my name isn't Amy Archer
and I never won the Pulitzer Prize.

579
00:40:08,199 --> 00:40:09,829
In 1957.

580
00:40:10,034 --> 00:40:13,294
My, oh, my series
on the reunited triplets.

581
00:40:13,496 --> 00:40:16,746
Well, come down here, hammerhead,
and I'll show it to you!

582
00:40:16,957 --> 00:40:19,287
What's a three-letter word
for a flightless bird?

583
00:40:19,502 --> 00:40:20,502
AMY:
Not now, I'm busy.

584
00:40:20,711 --> 00:40:23,671
Right, I said, "hammerhead,"
as in a 10-letter word for a smug...

585
00:40:23,881 --> 00:40:25,051
...bullying newspaper man.

586
00:40:25,257 --> 00:40:27,047
Gnu. Who couldn't find-- That's G-N-U.

587
00:40:27,259 --> 00:40:30,599
Couldn't find the Empire State Building
with a compass, map and a guide.

588
00:40:30,805 --> 00:40:33,765
Or is it Emu? That's just potatoes.
Here comes the gravy.

589
00:40:33,974 --> 00:40:35,274
The chump really likes me.

590
00:40:35,476 --> 00:40:38,346
- Ah. A Muncie girl!
- Better off falling for a rattlesnake.

591
00:40:38,562 --> 00:40:41,112
This guy's just a patsy
and I'm gonna find out what for.

592
00:40:41,315 --> 00:40:43,315
There's a real story here,
some kind of plot.

593
00:40:43,526 --> 00:40:45,486
A set-up.
Oh, and say, did I tell you?

594
00:40:45,694 --> 00:40:47,414
- He didn't offer you money?
- A sawbuck!

595
00:40:47,613 --> 00:40:49,573
Ten smackers! Let's grab a highball!

596
00:40:49,782 --> 00:40:51,452
- On Norville Barnes.
- Yeah.

597
00:40:51,659 --> 00:40:52,659
[AMY WHISTLES]

598
00:40:52,868 --> 00:40:54,408
Copy!

599
00:41:23,065 --> 00:41:25,145
Ms. Smith, would you come in
and take a letter?

600
00:41:26,527 --> 00:41:28,567
Of all the cockamamy...

601
00:41:30,448 --> 00:41:33,198
Did you see the front page
of today's Manhattan <i>Argus?</i>

602
00:41:33,409 --> 00:41:37,579
Well, I, uh, didn't bother to read the article.
I didn't think the picture did you justice.

603
00:41:38,289 --> 00:41:39,749
Well, the picture's fine.

604
00:41:39,957 --> 00:41:42,247
It's what that knuckle-headed
dame wrote underneath.

605
00:41:42,460 --> 00:41:44,920
Of all the irresponsible--
Take this down.

606
00:41:45,129 --> 00:41:47,209
Dear, Ms. Archer.

607
00:41:47,423 --> 00:41:50,973
I call you "Miss" because you seem
to have missed the boat completely.

608
00:41:51,177 --> 00:41:53,137
How would you know if I'm an imbecile?

609
00:41:53,345 --> 00:41:55,925
You didn't have the guts to come
interview me man-to-man!

610
00:41:56,140 --> 00:41:57,850
Change "man-to-man"
to "face-to-face."

611
00:41:58,058 --> 00:42:01,228
Change "face-to-face" to "eye-to-eye"
and "guts" to "common decency."

612
00:42:01,437 --> 00:42:03,557
These wild speculations
about my intelligence...

613
00:42:03,772 --> 00:42:06,072
...these preposterous inventions
would be suited...

614
00:42:06,275 --> 00:42:09,025
<i>...to the pages of
Amazing Tales Magazine.</i>

615
00:42:09,236 --> 00:42:11,486
If the editors of the <i>Manhattan Argus</i>
see fit...

616
00:42:11,697 --> 00:42:13,907
...to publish the rantings
of a disordered mind...

617
00:42:14,116 --> 00:42:16,486
...perhaps they will see fit
to publish this letter.

618
00:42:16,702 --> 00:42:18,122
But I most seriously doubt it.

619
00:42:18,329 --> 00:42:21,289
As I doubt also that you could find a home
at <i>Amazing</i> Tales...

620
00:42:21,499 --> 00:42:24,079
...a periodical which I have enjoyed
for many years.

621
00:42:24,293 --> 00:42:27,133
Sincerely, et cetera, et cetera,
et cetera.

622
00:42:33,802 --> 00:42:35,762
Is that all, Mr. Barnes?

623
00:42:35,971 --> 00:42:37,311
Uh...

624
00:42:37,890 --> 00:42:41,390
You know me, Amy, better than this dame.
Do you think I'm an imbecile?

625
00:42:41,810 --> 00:42:43,440
Oh, well, I'm sure I...

626
00:42:43,646 --> 00:42:46,856
Tell the truth. I trust you.
I place a lot of stock in your opinion.

627
00:42:48,317 --> 00:42:50,857
- Well...
- Oh, sure, heh, you're biased.

628
00:42:51,070 --> 00:42:52,110
You're a fellow Muncian, heh.

629
00:42:52,321 --> 00:42:53,321
Hmm.

630
00:42:53,531 --> 00:42:58,291
But let me ask you a question:
Would an imbecile come up with this?

631
00:43:04,041 --> 00:43:06,001
I designed it myself.

632
00:43:06,794 --> 00:43:10,344
This sweet baby will put
Hudsucker right back on top.

633
00:43:10,548 --> 00:43:11,878
Uh-huh.

634
00:43:12,633 --> 00:43:14,303
You know, for kids.

635
00:43:17,304 --> 00:43:19,604
Why don't I just type this up?

636
00:43:19,807 --> 00:43:22,637
Oh, no, Amy, that won't be necessary.
I shouldn't send it.

637
00:43:22,851 --> 00:43:25,151
She's just doing her job, I guess.

638
00:43:25,354 --> 00:43:27,864
I don't know, maybe she does deserve it.

639
00:43:28,065 --> 00:43:31,105
Maybe she should have come in here
and faced you man-to-man.

640
00:43:31,318 --> 00:43:32,318
NORVILLE:
She had a deadline.

641
00:43:32,528 --> 00:43:36,528
Sure, but she still could've gotten
your side, for the record.

642
00:43:36,740 --> 00:43:39,540
Well, it's done now. What's the use
of grousing about it? Ha, ha.

643
00:43:39,743 --> 00:43:42,963
Forget the letter, Amy,
I just had to blow off some steam. Heh.

644
00:43:43,163 --> 00:43:45,873
She's probably just a little confused.

645
00:43:46,417 --> 00:43:49,837
- Confused?
- She's probably a fast-talking career gal...

646
00:43:50,045 --> 00:43:52,755
...thinks she's one of the boys.
If you know what I mean, heh.

647
00:43:52,965 --> 00:43:55,505
Oh, I'm quite sure
I don't know what you mean.

648
00:43:55,718 --> 00:43:58,178
Suffers from one of these complexes
they have nowadays.

649
00:43:58,387 --> 00:43:59,677
Seems pretty obvious.

650
00:43:59,888 --> 00:44:02,468
She's probably very unattractive
and bitter about it.

651
00:44:02,683 --> 00:44:04,353
- Oh, is that it?
- Yeah.

652
00:44:04,560 --> 00:44:06,440
She probably dresses in men's clothing...

653
00:44:06,645 --> 00:44:08,725
...drinks with the guys
at the watering hole...

654
00:44:08,939 --> 00:44:11,399
...hobnobs with some smooth-talking
heel named Biff...

655
00:44:11,609 --> 00:44:13,359
...or Smoocher or, uh--
- Smitty.

656
00:44:13,569 --> 00:44:15,899
Exactly. I bet she's ugly, real ugly.

657
00:44:16,113 --> 00:44:18,623
Otherwise, why isn't her picture
next to her byline?

658
00:44:18,824 --> 00:44:22,124
Oh, maybe she puts her work
ahead of her personal appearance.

659
00:44:22,328 --> 00:44:24,408
I bet that's exactly what she tells herself.

660
00:44:24,622 --> 00:44:27,172
But you and I both know
she's a dried-up, bitter old maid.

661
00:44:27,374 --> 00:44:28,384
[CHUCKLES]

662
00:44:28,584 --> 00:44:30,754
Amy, how about we grab
a little dinner and a show after work?

663
00:44:30,961 --> 00:44:32,501
I was thinking maybe The King and I.

664
00:44:33,964 --> 00:44:35,344
<i>Uh, how about Oklahomal?</i>

665
00:44:35,549 --> 00:44:38,049
Norville, you don't know
a thing about that woman!

666
00:44:38,260 --> 00:44:39,760
You don't know who she really is.

667
00:44:39,970 --> 00:44:42,310
And only a numbskull thinks
he knows things...

668
00:44:42,514 --> 00:44:44,644
...about things he
knows nothing, uh, about.

669
00:44:46,644 --> 00:44:48,904
NORVILLE:
Say, what gives?

670
00:45:02,910 --> 00:45:05,700
[WHISTLING]

671
00:45:12,586 --> 00:45:14,796
[DOOR OPENS]

672
00:45:40,948 --> 00:45:42,028
Uh-huh.

673
00:45:42,700 --> 00:45:44,490
[CLOSES BOOK]

674
00:46:50,476 --> 00:46:53,806
[TALKING INDISTINCTLY]

675
00:46:55,355 --> 00:46:56,725
The inventory of the Jacksonville...

676
00:46:56,940 --> 00:47:00,240
...facility should be reduced
by 15 percent.

677
00:47:00,444 --> 00:47:02,404
Memo from the desk
of Sidney J. Mussburger--

678
00:47:02,613 --> 00:47:05,163
MAN: What are you doing down there,
Ms. Archer?

679
00:47:05,365 --> 00:47:06,985
Huh?

680
00:47:14,082 --> 00:47:17,292
Who are you?
How did you know who I am?

681
00:47:17,503 --> 00:47:19,253
[CHUCKLES]

682
00:47:19,463 --> 00:47:23,223
I suspect Old Moses knows
just about everything...

683
00:47:23,425 --> 00:47:26,215
...leastways if it concerns Hudsucker.

684
00:47:26,428 --> 00:47:28,558
But who are you?
What do you do here?

685
00:47:28,764 --> 00:47:33,894
I keep the old circle turning.
This old clock needs plenty of care.

686
00:47:34,102 --> 00:47:36,362
Time is money, Ms. Archer.

687
00:47:36,563 --> 00:47:39,193
And money drives
that old global economy...

688
00:47:39,399 --> 00:47:41,739
...and keeps Big Daddy Earth
spinning around.

689
00:47:41,944 --> 00:47:45,114
- See, without that capital formation--
- Yeah, yeah.

690
00:47:45,322 --> 00:47:48,742
Say, you won't tell anyone about me,
will you?

691
00:47:48,951 --> 00:47:53,961
I don't tell no one nothing
unless they ask.

692
00:47:54,164 --> 00:47:56,584
That just ain't Old Moses' way.

693
00:47:56,792 --> 00:47:58,752
So if you know
everything about Hudsucker...

694
00:47:58,961 --> 00:48:02,091
...tell me why the board decided
to make Norville Barnes president?

695
00:48:02,464 --> 00:48:05,554
Well, that even surprised Old Moses
at first.

696
00:48:05,759 --> 00:48:08,799
- I didn't think the board was that smart.
- "That smart"?

697
00:48:09,012 --> 00:48:10,932
But then I figured it out.

698
00:48:11,139 --> 00:48:14,179
They did it because they figured
young Norville for an imbecile...

699
00:48:14,393 --> 00:48:15,943
...like some other people I know.

700
00:48:16,436 --> 00:48:19,686
Now, why on earth would the board
want a nitwit to be president?

701
00:48:19,898 --> 00:48:24,108
Because they're little piglets.
They're trying to inspire panic...

702
00:48:24,319 --> 00:48:27,699
...make that stock cheap so they can
snatch it all up for themselves.

703
00:48:27,906 --> 00:48:32,076
But Norville, he's got some tricks up
his sleeve. He does.

704
00:48:32,286 --> 00:48:34,156
You know, for kids.

705
00:48:34,371 --> 00:48:35,461
- Hee-hee.
- Uh-huh.

706
00:48:35,664 --> 00:48:39,004
Yeah, he's a smart one, that Norville.

707
00:48:39,209 --> 00:48:42,629
But I guess you don't really know him
any better than that board does...

708
00:48:42,838 --> 00:48:43,798
...do you, Ms. Archer?

709
00:48:44,798 --> 00:48:47,628
- Well, maybe I--
- And only some kind of knuckle-head...

710
00:48:47,843 --> 00:48:50,643
...thinks she knows things
about things she, uh...

711
00:48:51,763 --> 00:48:54,393
When she don't, uh...

712
00:48:54,600 --> 00:48:57,940
- How'd that go?
- Well, it's hardly the same.

713
00:48:58,145 --> 00:49:00,605
Why, you don't even know
your own self.

714
00:49:00,814 --> 00:49:04,484
You ain't exactly the genuine article,
are you, Ms. Archer?

715
00:49:04,693 --> 00:49:06,823
Yes, well, in connection with my job...

716
00:49:07,029 --> 00:49:09,529
...sometimes I have to, uh, go undercover,
as it were.

717
00:49:09,740 --> 00:49:11,490
I don't mean that.

718
00:49:11,700 --> 00:49:15,660
Why are you pretending to be
such a hard old sourpuss?

719
00:49:15,871 --> 00:49:18,171
Ain't gonna
never make you happy.

720
00:49:20,083 --> 00:49:22,503
I'm happy enough.

721
00:49:22,711 --> 00:49:24,171
[LAUGHING]

722
00:49:24,755 --> 00:49:26,165
Okay, Ms. Archer.

723
00:49:27,716 --> 00:49:29,296
I got gears to see to.

724
00:49:29,509 --> 00:49:31,469
[LAUGHING]

725
00:49:34,473 --> 00:49:36,813
I'm plenty happy!

726
00:49:43,231 --> 00:49:44,691
AMY:
Hello?

727
00:49:46,902 --> 00:49:48,952
- I can't print that!
- Why not? It's all true.

728
00:49:49,154 --> 00:49:51,874
The board's using him to depress
the stock to buy it cheap.

729
00:49:52,074 --> 00:49:53,994
It's pure speculation!
They'd have my butt in a satchel!

730
00:49:54,201 --> 00:49:57,581
- Ah. Old satchel butt.
AMY: I know they're gonna buy that stock.

731
00:49:57,788 --> 00:49:59,248
You don't.
They haven't bought it.

732
00:49:59,456 --> 00:50:01,626
The stock's cheap!
What are they waiting for?

733
00:50:01,833 --> 00:50:04,293
- I don't know.
- Amy's hunches are usually pretty good.

734
00:50:04,503 --> 00:50:07,173
You don't accuse somebody of stock
manipulation on a hunch.

735
00:50:07,381 --> 00:50:09,681
The readers aren't interested
in sensationalism...

736
00:50:09,883 --> 00:50:12,723
...gossip, unsupported speculation!
Facts! Figures! Charts!

737
00:50:12,928 --> 00:50:14,888
Those are the tools
of the newspaper trade.

738
00:50:15,097 --> 00:50:18,177
It's as if you're trying to take the heat off
this Barnes numbskull.

739
00:50:18,392 --> 00:50:20,522
Oh, come on, chief. That's a low blow.

740
00:50:20,727 --> 00:50:23,357
Archer's not going to go gooey
for a corn-fed idiot.

741
00:50:23,563 --> 00:50:26,863
I was out of line. But you're out of line
with this stock-swindle story.

742
00:50:27,067 --> 00:50:29,277
Give me more of that
"moron from Sheboygan" stuff.

743
00:50:29,486 --> 00:50:30,856
- Muncie.
- Whatever.

744
00:50:31,071 --> 00:50:32,411
That's what sells newspapers!

745
00:50:32,614 --> 00:50:35,164
I've got a harder story,
"The Sap From The City Desk!"

746
00:50:35,367 --> 00:50:37,827
- Watch it!
- It's about a dim-witted editor who--

747
00:50:38,036 --> 00:50:40,036
Easy, tough guy. Heh-heh-heh.

748
00:50:42,749 --> 00:50:44,629
Does this suit look mannish to you?

749
00:50:44,835 --> 00:50:47,125
SMITTY:
Yeah, sure. Let's grab a highball.

750
00:50:47,963 --> 00:50:49,173
AMY:
Back off!

751
00:50:49,381 --> 00:50:51,091
Smoocher!

752
00:50:52,342 --> 00:50:55,352
Eh. What gives?

753
00:51:05,731 --> 00:51:07,691
[CHATTERING]

754
00:51:10,485 --> 00:51:13,905
A man of great managerial potency.

755
00:51:14,114 --> 00:51:16,454
My husband is also a president.

756
00:51:16,658 --> 00:51:19,948
Sears Braithwaite of Bullard.
Do you know him?

757
00:51:20,162 --> 00:51:22,502
Your companion is an ode!

758
00:51:22,706 --> 00:51:25,126
A lyric! Are you betrothed?

759
00:51:25,333 --> 00:51:27,713
Amy works in my office.
She runs, uh...

760
00:51:27,919 --> 00:51:32,259
- Oh, the folly of youth.
- Those green remembered hills.

761
00:51:32,466 --> 00:51:35,886
That bourn
from which no traveler returns.

762
00:51:36,094 --> 00:51:38,224
I once ran the mimeograph
for Sidney.

763
00:51:38,430 --> 00:51:41,730
Though engaged at the time
to quelqu'un d'autre...

764
00:51:41,933 --> 00:51:45,653
...my water-cooler romance
became a mad passion.

765
00:51:45,854 --> 00:51:48,864
<i>Uh. An amour fou.
A folie à deux.</i>

766
00:51:49,066 --> 00:51:50,776
[LAUGHS]

767
00:51:50,984 --> 00:51:53,654
I'm brushing up on my French
with the most charming man...

768
00:51:53,862 --> 00:51:55,362
...Pierre of 5th Avenue.
- Oh!

769
00:51:55,572 --> 00:51:57,162
- Do you know him?
- Do you know him?

770
00:51:57,365 --> 00:52:02,325
Sidney and I are planning a trip
to Paris and points continental.

771
00:52:02,537 --> 00:52:03,867
[WOMEN LAUGHING]

772
00:52:05,499 --> 00:52:06,499
- Oh.
- Aren't we, clear?

773
00:52:07,542 --> 00:52:12,672
For sure. I would like to borrow Norville
for a while, if you don't mind, dear.

774
00:52:12,881 --> 00:52:15,631
Oh, well, uh, frankly, I...

775
00:52:15,842 --> 00:52:17,682
You have a very charming wife,
Mr.-- Sid.

776
00:52:17,886 --> 00:52:19,506
So they tell me.

777
00:52:19,721 --> 00:52:23,231
Norville, let me shepherd you
through some of the introductions here.

778
00:52:23,433 --> 00:52:25,523
Try not to talk too much.

779
00:52:25,727 --> 00:52:28,187
Some of our biggest stockholders are...

780
00:52:28,396 --> 00:52:30,146
Scratch that. Say whatever you like.

781
00:52:30,357 --> 00:52:32,647
Shake hands here
with Sears Braithwaite of Bullard.

782
00:52:32,859 --> 00:52:35,149
- Sir.
- Glad to know you, Barnes.

783
00:52:35,362 --> 00:52:37,032
MUSSBURGER:
And this is Zebulon Cardozo...

784
00:52:37,239 --> 00:52:40,239
...one of Hudsucker's largest
and most loyal stockholders.

785
00:52:40,450 --> 00:52:42,540
What's this I hear
about you being an imbecile?

786
00:52:42,744 --> 00:52:44,544
What's ailing you, boy?

787
00:52:44,746 --> 00:52:47,746
Last week, my stock
was worth twice what it is now.

788
00:52:47,958 --> 00:52:50,668
I'm getting out of the whole
kit and caboodle of it, boy...

789
00:52:50,877 --> 00:52:53,257
...unless I see a
vast improvement.

790
00:52:53,463 --> 00:52:56,223
What you've got here, son,
is a range war!

791
00:52:56,424 --> 00:53:00,184
You're gonna have to circle our wagons
or I'm gonna get out of your wagon train.

792
00:53:00,387 --> 00:53:01,557
[CHUCKLES]

793
00:53:01,763 --> 00:53:02,893
No need for concern, sir.

794
00:53:03,098 --> 00:53:05,178
It's only natural in a period
of transition...

795
00:53:05,392 --> 00:53:07,192
...for the more timid elements
to run.

796
00:53:07,394 --> 00:53:10,194
Yellow? I'll show you yellow, boy!

797
00:53:10,397 --> 00:53:13,897
Zebulon, you mind now and quit acting
like such an old grizzly.

798
00:53:14,109 --> 00:53:16,569
MUSSBURGER:
Step lively here, Norville.

799
00:53:16,778 --> 00:53:19,738
I'm sorry, Sid, uh, I thought maybe
if I showed him the long view...

800
00:53:19,948 --> 00:53:22,828
And this is Thorstenson Finlandson...

801
00:53:23,034 --> 00:53:25,954
...who heads a radical splinter group
of disgruntled investors.

802
00:53:26,163 --> 00:53:27,833
Ah. Pleased to meet you,
Mr. Finlandson.

803
00:53:28,039 --> 00:53:30,709
It might interest you to know I studied
Finnish in high school.

804
00:53:30,917 --> 00:53:32,877
Let see,
I hope I'm not too rusty. Um...

805
00:53:34,087 --> 00:53:36,547
[SPEAKS IN FINNISH]

806
00:53:36,756 --> 00:53:38,216
[WOMAN SCREAMS]

807
00:53:40,886 --> 00:53:41,926
Ladies and gentlemen...

808
00:53:42,137 --> 00:53:44,347
...distinguished members
of the Hudsucker board...

809
00:53:44,556 --> 00:53:48,596
...I give you the Rajah of Romance,
the Ministereo of Moonlight...

810
00:53:48,810 --> 00:53:51,100
...the incredible,
the unforgettable...

811
00:53:51,313 --> 00:53:55,193
...Mr. Vic Tenetta!

812
00:53:55,483 --> 00:53:57,823
[CROWD APPLAUDING]

813
00:53:58,111 --> 00:54:00,571
[CHORUS HUMMING]

814
00:54:00,864 --> 00:54:04,124
Rajah, I like that.

815
00:54:04,326 --> 00:54:09,076
[SINGING]
<i>Take one fresh and tender kiss</i>

816
00:54:09,289 --> 00:54:11,119
[GASPS]

817
00:54:11,333 --> 00:54:17,303
<i>Add one stolen night of bliss</i>

818
00:54:18,924 --> 00:54:25,514
<i>One girl one boy
Some grief some joy</i>

819
00:54:25,722 --> 00:54:31,022
<i>Memories are made of this</i>

820
00:54:32,854 --> 00:54:34,484
<i>Don 't</i>

821
00:54:40,528 --> 00:54:41,488
Norville?

822
00:54:45,659 --> 00:54:47,239
What happened?

823
00:54:47,452 --> 00:54:53,292
Oh, nothing. Just the more timid investors
are no longer running for cover.

824
00:54:53,500 --> 00:54:56,250
- Let me look.
- Sid found me the ice pack.

825
00:54:56,461 --> 00:54:58,961
Well, let me hold it
or you'll have a real shiner.

826
00:54:59,172 --> 00:55:00,382
Oh, thanks.

827
00:55:00,590 --> 00:55:03,680
I guess people are pretty hot
over this imbecile story.

828
00:55:03,885 --> 00:55:05,465
I'm sorry.

829
00:55:05,679 --> 00:55:06,969
Oh, it's not your fault, Amy.

830
00:55:07,180 --> 00:55:09,600
You're the one person
standing by me through this.

831
00:55:09,808 --> 00:55:13,438
Norville, there's something
I have to tell you.

832
00:55:13,645 --> 00:55:17,765
You see, I'm not really a secretary.

833
00:55:18,441 --> 00:55:20,741
- I know that, Amy.
- You do?

834
00:55:20,944 --> 00:55:24,034
I understand you're not very skilled yet
in the secretarial arts...

835
00:55:24,239 --> 00:55:27,199
...but I'll tell you a secret,
I'm not that skilled as president.

836
00:55:27,409 --> 00:55:31,619
- I know I put up a big front, but, uh--
- I believe in you, Norville.

837
00:55:32,455 --> 00:55:36,535
At least, I believe in your intentions.

838
00:55:36,751 --> 00:55:40,591
Oh, I don't blame them, really.
I suppose I have made a mess of things.

839
00:55:40,797 --> 00:55:42,877
Those folks have to protect
their investment.

840
00:55:43,091 --> 00:55:44,721
Most of them are very nice people.

841
00:55:44,926 --> 00:55:48,176
Listen, Norville, you can't trust people here
like you did in Muncie.

842
00:55:48,388 --> 00:55:50,218
Certain people are...

843
00:55:50,432 --> 00:55:54,232
See, did you ever go to the top of Larson's
feed tower and look out over the town?

844
00:55:54,436 --> 00:55:56,896
- What?
- On Farm Route 17?

845
00:55:57,105 --> 00:55:59,645
Oh, yes, in Muncie.

846
00:56:00,775 --> 00:56:06,445
- No, Vidalia. Farm Route 17.
- Oh, yes, 17, yes.

847
00:56:06,656 --> 00:56:08,866
I... Well, no, no. I never really.

848
00:56:09,075 --> 00:56:10,235
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

849
00:56:10,452 --> 00:56:14,292
The guys from the Varsity Squad
would bring their dates up there to...

850
00:56:15,290 --> 00:56:17,000
...hold hands.

851
00:56:17,208 --> 00:56:20,748
Of course, I never made Varsity.

852
00:56:22,464 --> 00:56:24,764
There's a place I go now.

853
00:56:24,966 --> 00:56:27,886
Cutest little place near my apartment
in Greenwich Village.

854
00:56:28,094 --> 00:56:31,644
It's called Ann's 440. It's a beatnik bar.

855
00:56:31,848 --> 00:56:33,428
- You don't say?
- Yes.

856
00:56:33,641 --> 00:56:35,601
- A beatnik bar.
- You can get carrot juice...

857
00:56:35,810 --> 00:56:40,770
...or Italian coffee and the people there,
well, none of them quite fit in.

858
00:56:40,982 --> 00:56:41,942
You'd love it.

859
00:56:42,650 --> 00:56:44,190
Why don't you come there with me?

860
00:56:44,402 --> 00:56:47,782
There's a marathon poetry-reading
on New Year's Eve. I go every year.

861
00:56:47,989 --> 00:56:50,119
- It's marvelous.
- Every year?

862
00:56:51,993 --> 00:56:56,623
Well, this year, if it's good,
I plan to make it a tradition, heh.

863
00:56:56,831 --> 00:56:58,501
I! uh! heh...

864
00:56:58,708 --> 00:57:05,588
My, it certainly is beautiful.
The people look like ants.

865
00:57:06,091 --> 00:57:09,641
Well, the Hindus say,
and the beatniks also...

866
00:57:09,844 --> 00:57:12,974
...that in our next lives some of us
will come back as ants.

867
00:57:13,181 --> 00:57:15,771
Some will be butterflies,
others will be elephants...

868
00:57:15,975 --> 00:57:17,265
...or creatures of the sea.

869
00:57:17,477 --> 00:57:18,847
What a beautiful thought.

870
00:57:19,062 --> 00:57:22,652
Hey, what do you think you were
in a previous life, Amy?

871
00:57:22,857 --> 00:57:27,067
Oh, I don't know. Maybe I was just, uh...

872
00:57:27,278 --> 00:57:31,158
...a fast-talking career gal
who thought she was one of the boys.

873
00:57:31,366 --> 00:57:32,776
Oh, HO,

874
00:57:32,992 --> 00:57:35,702
Pardon me for saying so,
but I find that very far-fetched.

875
00:57:35,912 --> 00:57:38,502
- No, I have to tell you--
- That person would come back...

876
00:57:38,706 --> 00:57:40,076
...as a wildebeest or a warthog.

877
00:57:40,291 --> 00:57:45,881
No, I find it more likely
that you were a gazelle...

878
00:57:46,089 --> 00:57:50,389
...with long, graceful legs,
gamboling through the underbrush.

879
00:57:50,593 --> 00:57:52,723
Perhaps we met once.

880
00:57:52,929 --> 00:57:56,599
A chance encounter in a forest glade.

881
00:57:57,559 --> 00:58:01,149
I must have been an antelope
or an ibex.

882
00:58:01,354 --> 00:58:05,484
The times we must've had foraging
together for sustenance...

883
00:58:05,692 --> 00:58:08,862
...snorfling water
from a mountain stream...

884
00:58:09,070 --> 00:58:13,660
...picking the grubs and burrs
from one another's coats.

885
00:58:15,243 --> 00:58:21,043
Or perhaps we simply touched horns
briefly and went our separate ways.

886
00:58:21,249 --> 00:58:24,999
Oh, I wish it were that simple,
Norville.

887
00:58:25,211 --> 00:58:30,091
I wish I was still a gazelle
and you were an antelope...

888
00:58:30,300 --> 00:58:32,680
...or an ibex.

889
00:58:34,053 --> 00:58:35,813
Well...

890
00:58:36,639 --> 00:58:39,229
...can I at least call you "deer?"

891
00:58:39,434 --> 00:58:42,404
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

892
00:58:42,604 --> 00:58:43,654
You're funny.

893
00:58:43,855 --> 00:58:47,105
Seriously, Amy, it's what
your beatnik friends call "karma."

894
00:58:47,317 --> 00:58:50,527
- Karma.
- The great circle of life, death and rebirth.

895
00:58:50,737 --> 00:58:55,237
Yes, I think I heard of that.
What goes around, comes around.

896
00:58:55,450 --> 00:58:59,250
That's it. A great wheel
that gives us all what we deserve.

897
00:58:59,996 --> 00:59:03,076
I gotta show Sid
and all the guys I deserve their confidence.

898
00:59:03,291 --> 00:59:05,711
Tomorrow's my big presentation
to the board.

899
00:59:05,919 --> 00:59:07,669
[MOANS]

900
00:59:08,254 --> 00:59:11,764
Kiss me, Amy! Kiss me once for luck.

901
00:59:12,884 --> 00:59:16,554
Sure, Norville, sure.

902
00:59:50,380 --> 00:59:52,170
Shh.

903
00:59:55,635 --> 00:59:57,215
NORVILLE:
You know, for kids!

904
00:59:57,428 --> 00:59:59,638
It has economy, simplicity,
low production cost...

905
00:59:59,847 --> 01:00:01,137
...potential for mass appeal.

906
01:00:01,349 --> 01:00:03,309
All that spells out great profitability.

907
01:00:03,518 --> 01:00:06,308
I had the boys down at R&D
throw together this prototype...

908
01:00:06,521 --> 01:00:08,521
...so our discussion
could have some focus...

909
01:00:08,731 --> 01:00:12,191
...and to give you gentleman a firsthand
look at how exciting this gizmo is.

910
01:00:12,402 --> 01:00:15,662
It's fun, healthy, good exercise,
and the kids will just love it.

911
01:00:15,863 --> 01:00:18,833
We put a little sand inside
to make the experience more pleasant.

912
01:00:19,033 --> 01:00:22,333
But the great part is
we don't have to charge an arm and a leg.

913
01:00:25,039 --> 01:00:26,749
What if you tire before it's done?

914
01:00:26,958 --> 01:00:27,958
Does it have rules?

915
01:00:28,167 --> 01:00:30,127
MAN 1: Can more than one play?
MAN 2: It's a game?

916
01:00:30,336 --> 01:00:31,626
MAN 3: Is it a game?
ADDISON: Will it break?

917
01:00:31,838 --> 01:00:34,168
MAN 4: It better break eventually.
MAN 5: Is there an object?

918
01:00:34,382 --> 01:00:37,012
MAN 6: What if you tire before it's done?
MAN 7: Does it have batteries?

919
01:00:37,218 --> 01:00:39,468
MAN 8: Could we charge extra for them?
ADDISON: Is it safe for toddlers?

920
01:00:39,846 --> 01:00:41,306
MAN 2:
How do you know you're finished?

921
01:00:41,514 --> 01:00:42,524
MAN 5:
How does it stop?

922
01:00:42,724 --> 01:00:44,984
MAN 8: Is that a boy's model?
MAN 9: Can a parent assemble it?

923
01:00:45,184 --> 01:00:49,024
MAN 4: What if you tire before it's done?
MAN 7: Is there a larger model for the obese?

924
01:00:49,230 --> 01:00:51,440
What the hell is it?

925
01:00:51,649 --> 01:00:55,239
Well, it's a... It's a...

926
01:00:55,445 --> 01:00:56,445
It's a...

927
01:00:56,654 --> 01:00:57,704
MUSSBURGER:
Brilliant!

928
01:00:59,616 --> 01:01:01,196
Genius.

929
01:01:01,868 --> 01:01:05,368
It's exactly what Hudsucker Industry
needs at this juncture.

930
01:01:05,580 --> 01:01:06,710
Sure, sure.

931
01:01:06,914 --> 01:01:11,924
Even a blind man can tell you there'll be
an enormous demand for this, uh...

932
01:01:12,295 --> 01:01:13,915
This...

933
01:01:14,130 --> 01:01:15,210
Congratulations, kid.

934
01:01:15,423 --> 01:01:17,843
You've outdone yourself.
You've reinvented the wheel.

935
01:01:18,051 --> 01:01:22,601
I'll recommend to the board that we
proceed immediately and that the, uh...

936
01:01:22,805 --> 01:01:24,845
And that the, uh...

937
01:01:25,683 --> 01:01:28,563
...dingus be mass-produced
with all deliberate speed.

938
01:01:28,770 --> 01:01:30,860
Although, you realize...

939
01:01:31,064 --> 01:01:33,074
...of course...

940
01:01:35,568 --> 01:01:37,238
...as president...

941
01:01:37,445 --> 01:01:40,195
...the ultimate decision is yours.

942
01:01:40,406 --> 01:01:42,486
Oh. I'm for it.

943
01:01:46,537 --> 01:01:48,917
[BELL RINGING]

944
01:02:29,288 --> 01:02:31,788
MAN 1:
We'll call it the Flying Doughnut!

945
01:02:31,999 --> 01:02:32,959
MAN 2:
The Dancing Dingus!

946
01:02:33,167 --> 01:02:34,457
MAN 1:
The Belly-Go-Round.

947
01:02:34,669 --> 01:02:35,629
MAN 2:
The Swingerina!

948
01:02:35,837 --> 01:02:39,127
MAN 1: The Wacky Circumference!
MAN 2: Uncle Midriff!

949
01:03:10,079 --> 01:03:11,749
MAN 1: We need something short!
MAN 2: Sharp!

950
01:03:11,956 --> 01:03:13,496
MAN 1: Snappy!
MAN 2: With a little jazz!

951
01:03:13,708 --> 01:03:14,828
MAN 1:
The Shazzammeter!

952
01:03:15,042 --> 01:03:16,042
MAN 2:
The Hipster!

953
01:03:16,252 --> 01:03:17,592
MAN 1:
The Daddy-O!

954
01:03:20,840 --> 01:03:22,680
[BELL RINGING]

955
01:03:58,920 --> 01:04:00,630
MAN 1: The Hoopsucker.
MAN 2: The Hudswinger.

956
01:04:00,838 --> 01:04:04,218
MAN 1: The Hoopsucker!
MAN 2: The Hudswinger!

957
01:04:25,446 --> 01:04:28,066
MAN 1: The Hoopsucker!
MAN 2: The Hudswinger!

958
01:04:28,282 --> 01:04:30,082
MAN 1: The Hoopsucker!
MAN 2: The Hudswinger!

959
01:04:30,284 --> 01:04:33,794
MAN 3: Fellas!
MAN 2: You got something?

960
01:04:33,996 --> 01:04:35,076
MAN 1:
You got something?

961
01:04:35,289 --> 01:04:38,249
MAN 3:
Fella, I got something!

962
01:04:49,971 --> 01:04:51,471
[WHISTLES]

963
01:04:52,014 --> 01:04:53,024
Ladies.

964
01:06:19,727 --> 01:06:21,307
[SCHOOL BELL RINGS]

965
01:06:21,520 --> 01:06:23,480
[ALL CHEERING]

966
01:07:15,157 --> 01:07:17,117
[ALL CHEERING]

967
01:07:25,584 --> 01:07:27,294
Wow.

968
01:07:41,976 --> 01:07:43,766
Norville!

969
01:07:50,192 --> 01:07:54,612
NEWSCASTER [OVER TV]:
Rockwell News presents, Tidbits of Time.

970
01:07:54,822 --> 01:07:57,622
<i>World news in pictures,
we kid you not.</i>

971
01:07:57,825 --> 01:08:01,445
<i>As Old Man 1958
hobbles towards his finish...</i>

972
01:08:01,662 --> 01:08:04,122
<i>...Barnes is the name
on every American lip.</i>

973
01:08:04,331 --> 01:08:07,671
<i>Norville Barnes, young president
of Hudsucker Industries...</i>

974
01:08:07,877 --> 01:08:11,757
<i>...a boy bred in the heartland,
but now the toast of New York.</i>

975
01:08:11,964 --> 01:08:15,304
<i>Barnes is the brainy inventor
of America's craziest craze:</i>

976
01:08:15,509 --> 01:08:16,839
<i>The Hula-Hoop!</i>

977
01:08:17,053 --> 01:08:20,473
<i>Reaping huge profits for his company
and winning the hearts...</i>

978
01:08:20,681 --> 01:08:23,771
<i>...and hips of every youngster
in America!</i>

979
01:08:23,976 --> 01:08:26,556
<i>Woo-ho. Did I say youngster?</i>

980
01:08:26,771 --> 01:08:30,071
<i>Here's Mom taking a break
from her household chores...</i>

981
01:08:30,274 --> 01:08:33,824
<i>...and even Dad is swinging
into the act!</i>

982
01:08:34,695 --> 01:08:36,485
<i>Cards, letters, congratulations...</i>

983
01:08:36,697 --> 01:08:39,657
<i>...come pouring
in from Kankakee to Petaluma...</i>

984
01:08:39,867 --> 01:08:42,947
<i>...including one very special
long-distance call.</i>

985
01:08:43,162 --> 01:08:45,872
He's on! He's on the line!

986
01:08:46,040 --> 01:08:48,290
[ALL CHATTERING IN DISTINCTLY]

987
01:08:51,545 --> 01:08:52,665
- Hello?
EISENHOWER: Hello, Norville.

988
01:08:52,880 --> 01:08:54,720
<i>- This is the President.
- Oh, my God, sir.</i>

989
01:08:54,924 --> 01:08:57,844
<i>I just wanted to congratulate you.
I'm very proud of you.</i>

990
01:08:58,052 --> 01:09:01,262
<i>- Oh, my God, sir.
- Mrs. Eisenhower is very proud of you.</i>

991
01:09:01,472 --> 01:09:04,432
<i>The American people
are very proud of you.</i>

992
01:09:05,017 --> 01:09:06,937
[ALL CHATTERING]

993
01:09:09,939 --> 01:09:14,109
REPORTER: Mr. Barnes, how'd you come
up with the idea for the Hula-Hoop?

994
01:09:14,318 --> 01:09:16,028
It was no great idea, really.

995
01:09:16,237 --> 01:09:18,737
A thing like this takes a whole company
to put together.

996
01:09:18,948 --> 01:09:20,528
I'm grateful for the opportunity.

997
01:09:20,741 --> 01:09:23,451
Did you have any idea
there'd be such a huge response?

998
01:09:23,661 --> 01:09:26,911
Frankly, I don't think anybody
expected this much hoopla.

999
01:09:27,081 --> 01:09:28,331
[ALL LAUGH]

1000
01:09:28,541 --> 01:09:31,961
"Hoopla on the Hula-Hoop."
Can we quote you on that, Mr. Barnes?

1001
01:09:32,169 --> 01:09:33,209
Sure, I guess.

1002
01:09:33,420 --> 01:09:36,630
Mr. Barnes, will you give yourself a nice,
fat raise?

1003
01:09:36,841 --> 01:09:37,841
[ALL CHUCKLE]

1004
01:09:38,050 --> 01:09:39,510
NORVILLE:
Come on, you guys.

1005
01:09:46,225 --> 01:09:49,395
<i>ANNOUNCER 1: What scientific principle
explains the mind-bending motion...</i>

1006
01:09:49,603 --> 01:09:51,403
<i>...of this whipping wheel of wonder?</i>

1007
01:09:51,605 --> 01:09:53,605
The dingus is quite simple, really.

1008
01:09:53,816 --> 01:09:55,526
It operates on the same principles...

1009
01:09:55,734 --> 01:09:58,034
...that keep the Earth spinning
around the sun...

1010
01:09:58,237 --> 01:10:00,817
...and that keeps you
from flying off the Earth...

1011
01:10:01,031 --> 01:10:02,701
...into the cold reaches of space...

1012
01:10:02,908 --> 01:10:05,198
...where you would die
like a miserable swine.

1013
01:10:05,411 --> 01:10:07,791
Yes, the principle is the same...

1014
01:10:07,997 --> 01:10:12,787
...except for the piece of grit
they put in to make the experience...

1015
01:10:13,002 --> 01:10:14,382
...more pleasant.

1016
01:10:14,587 --> 01:10:16,877
<i>ANNOUNCER 2:
Yes, it's Hula-Hula everywhere!</i>

1017
01:10:17,089 --> 01:10:19,589
<i>From the parties of the Park Avenue
smart set...</i>

1018
01:10:23,262 --> 01:10:26,852
<i>...to sweethearts who want to be married
in the swing of things.</i>

1019
01:10:29,768 --> 01:10:32,148
Mr. Barnes, did the board
consider you an idea man...

1020
01:10:32,354 --> 01:10:34,484
...when they promoted you
from the mailroom?

1021
01:10:34,690 --> 01:10:38,280
I guess so, I don't think they promoted me
because they thought I was a schmo.

1022
01:10:38,485 --> 01:10:41,235
Mr. Barnes, what's the next big idea
for you and Hudsucker?

1023
01:10:41,447 --> 01:10:42,447
NORVILLE:
Jesus, I don't know.

1024
01:10:42,656 --> 01:10:45,026
An idea like this sweet baby
doesn't just come overnight.

1025
01:10:45,242 --> 01:10:49,162
Although, I'll tell you one thing,
I certainly didn't expect all this hoopla.

1026
01:10:49,371 --> 01:10:50,331
[CHUCKLES]

1027
01:10:50,539 --> 01:10:51,499
You can quote me on that.

1028
01:10:58,964 --> 01:11:01,804
REPORTER: Rumpus Magazine
has called you the most eligible bachelor.

1029
01:11:02,009 --> 01:11:04,969
And society pages have been linking you
with fashion model Za-Za.

1030
01:11:05,179 --> 01:11:07,639
- You care to comment?
- There's no truth to the rumors.

1031
01:11:07,848 --> 01:11:10,388
We're just dear friends.
Isn't that right, Za-Za?

1032
01:11:12,311 --> 01:11:13,901
[GROWLS]
Wow.

1033
01:11:14,104 --> 01:11:15,314
REPORTERS:
Ooh.

1034
01:11:16,190 --> 01:11:19,490
Whoa. How do you respond to the charges
that you're out of ideas?

1035
01:11:19,693 --> 01:11:21,323
Has Norville Barnes run dry?

1036
01:11:21,528 --> 01:11:25,368
Not at all. Just this week I came up
with several new sweet ideas.

1037
01:11:25,574 --> 01:11:30,084
A larger model Hula-Hoop for the portly,
a battery option for the lazy or spastic.

1038
01:11:30,287 --> 01:11:32,827
A model with extra sand
for the hard-of-hearing.

1039
01:11:33,040 --> 01:11:34,250
I'm earning my keep.

1040
01:11:34,458 --> 01:11:36,788
Speaking of that,
do you expect to get a raise?

1041
01:11:37,002 --> 01:11:41,342
By anyone's account, I single-handedly
have saved Hudsucker Industries.

1042
01:11:41,548 --> 01:11:43,508
Our stock is worth more now than ever.

1043
01:11:43,717 --> 01:11:46,427
Yes, I expect to be compensated for that.

1044
01:12:00,234 --> 01:12:02,404
[SOBBING]

1045
01:12:05,948 --> 01:12:10,158
- Pull yourself together, man.
- Nobody told me!

1046
01:12:10,369 --> 01:12:12,999
You sold all our stock?

1047
01:12:13,205 --> 01:12:14,415
We dumped the whole load.

1048
01:12:14,623 --> 01:12:17,583
I had 20,000 shares!

1049
01:12:17,793 --> 01:12:19,503
I'd be a millionaire now.

1050
01:12:19,712 --> 01:12:22,212
MUSSBURGER:
Sure. We'd all be millionaires.

1051
01:12:22,423 --> 01:12:24,053
There's no point in looking back.

1052
01:12:25,342 --> 01:12:28,892
At the time, Stillson thought dumping
our position would panic the market...

1053
01:12:29,096 --> 01:12:31,306
...further depress the stock.

1054
01:12:31,515 --> 01:12:35,055
Then we could buy it back and more,
of course, once it got cheap.

1055
01:12:35,269 --> 01:12:39,109
Cheap? It's never been more valuable!

1056
01:12:40,274 --> 01:12:43,784
And I'm ruined. Ruined!

1057
01:12:48,741 --> 01:12:49,741
Addison.

1058
01:12:50,492 --> 01:12:54,082
I'm getting off this merry-go-round!

1059
01:12:54,288 --> 01:12:56,078
MAN:
Myron.

1060
01:13:03,881 --> 01:13:05,051
Plexiglas.

1061
01:13:05,632 --> 01:13:07,592
Had it installed last week.

1062
01:13:17,644 --> 01:13:18,654
Myron?

1063
01:13:18,854 --> 01:13:23,984
All right, so the kid caught a wave.

1064
01:13:24,693 --> 01:13:28,663
Right now, he and his dingus are on top.

1065
01:13:28,864 --> 01:13:31,034
Well, this too shall pass.

1066
01:13:31,492 --> 01:13:35,002
Myrtle J. Mussburger
did not raise her boy to go...

1067
01:13:35,204 --> 01:13:37,754
...knock-kneed
at the first sign of adversity.

1068
01:13:37,956 --> 01:13:41,536
I say, we made this chump,
we can break him!

1069
01:13:41,752 --> 01:13:45,302
I say, the higher he climbs,
the harder he drops!

1070
01:13:46,382 --> 01:13:48,092
I say, yes...

1071
01:13:48,300 --> 01:13:51,050
...the kid has a future...

1072
01:13:51,470 --> 01:13:53,140
...and in it...

1073
01:13:53,722 --> 01:13:56,102
...I see shame, dishonor...

1074
01:13:56,308 --> 01:13:59,398
...ignominy, disgrace.

1075
01:13:59,728 --> 01:14:01,858
Sure, sure.

1076
01:14:02,064 --> 01:14:05,654
The music plays, the wheel turns...

1077
01:14:05,859 --> 01:14:08,739
...and our spin ain't over yet.

1078
01:14:08,946 --> 01:14:10,906
[PLAYING CLASSICAL MUSIC]

1079
01:14:32,511 --> 01:14:34,301
For Pete's sakes, Norville!

1080
01:14:34,513 --> 01:14:36,683
NORVILLE:
Oh, Amy, where have you been hiding?

1081
01:14:36,890 --> 01:14:40,100
Do you know what those nincompoops
in the boardroom are doing?

1082
01:14:40,310 --> 01:14:42,150
I wouldn't call them nincompoops.

1083
01:14:42,354 --> 01:14:44,614
They're discharging 80 percent
of the workforce.

1084
01:14:44,815 --> 01:14:47,645
In New York City alone,
that means 1800 people out of work!

1085
01:14:47,860 --> 01:14:49,450
People with wives, children and families!

1086
01:14:49,653 --> 01:14:52,703
Oh, yes, we're pruning away
some of the dead wood.

1087
01:14:52,906 --> 01:14:56,236
- You mean you know about this?
- Know about it? Sure.

1088
01:14:56,452 --> 01:14:59,412
You think the board would do anything
without my authorization?

1089
01:14:59,621 --> 01:15:01,211
It was my idea from the start.

1090
01:15:01,415 --> 01:15:02,705
- Your--
- Sure, it was.

1091
01:15:02,916 --> 01:15:05,536
We're in a period of transition here.
Things have slowed.

1092
01:15:05,752 --> 01:15:08,262
You're being awfully kind to yourself,
Norville Barnes.

1093
01:15:08,464 --> 01:15:12,054
You've slowed down, sitting up
here like a sultan, not doing a lick of work.

1094
01:15:12,259 --> 01:15:14,719
You know ideas
are the lifeblood of industry...

1095
01:15:14,928 --> 01:15:17,218
...and you haven't come up with one since
the Hoop.

1096
01:15:17,431 --> 01:15:20,021
You've forgotten what made your ideas
exciting to you.

1097
01:15:20,225 --> 01:15:22,475
If it wasn't for the fame, wealth,
the adulation--

1098
01:15:22,686 --> 01:15:24,056
Would you get out of here?

1099
01:15:24,271 --> 01:15:27,401
You too, sisters, move it. Out, out, out!

1100
01:15:28,400 --> 01:15:31,400
I've been watching you, even though
you've been avoiding me.

1101
01:15:31,612 --> 01:15:32,572
AMY:
Shut up!

1102
01:15:32,779 --> 01:15:35,029
Don't think I haven't noticed
how you've changed.

1103
01:15:35,240 --> 01:15:36,910
I used to think you were a swell guy.

1104
01:15:37,117 --> 01:15:38,907
I thought you were an imbecile.

1105
01:15:39,119 --> 01:15:40,119
- Amy! I'm--
'Shut up!

1106
01:15:40,329 --> 01:15:43,619
Then I figured out you were a swell guy.
A little slow, but a swell guy.

1107
01:15:43,832 --> 01:15:47,172
Maybe you're not so slow, oh,
but you're not so swell either.

1108
01:15:47,377 --> 01:15:49,757
Looks like you're an imbecile,
after all. Shut up!

1109
01:15:49,963 --> 01:15:53,633
You haven't talked to me for a week
and now I'm going to say my piece.

1110
01:15:53,842 --> 01:15:56,602
Look, I've never been...

1111
01:15:56,803 --> 01:15:59,603
...dumped by a fella before,
and that hurts...

1112
01:15:59,806 --> 01:16:02,426
...but what really hurts is watching you
outrun your soul!

1113
01:16:02,643 --> 01:16:05,273
Chasing after money and ease
and the respect of a board...

1114
01:16:05,479 --> 01:16:07,859
...that wouldn't give you the time
of clay if you...

1115
01:16:08,065 --> 01:16:10,605
- If you...
- Worked in a watch factory?

1116
01:16:10,817 --> 01:16:12,107
[CHUCKLES]

1117
01:16:12,319 --> 01:16:14,029
Shut up! Exactly.

1118
01:16:14,780 --> 01:16:18,450
Norville, don't you remember
how you used to feel about the Hoop?

1119
01:16:18,659 --> 01:16:22,409
You told me you'd gonna bring a smile
to the hips of everyone in America...

1120
01:16:22,621 --> 01:16:24,621
...regardless of race, creed or color.

1121
01:16:24,831 --> 01:16:28,131
Finally, there'd be a thingamajig
that would bring everyone together...

1122
01:16:28,335 --> 01:16:30,955
...even if it kept them apart spatially.

1123
01:16:31,171 --> 01:16:33,971
"You know, for kids."

1124
01:16:34,758 --> 01:16:38,298
Your words, Norville, not mine.

1125
01:16:39,179 --> 01:16:41,059
I used to love Norville Barnes.

1126
01:16:41,890 --> 01:16:44,140
Yes, love him...

1127
01:16:44,351 --> 01:16:48,021
...when he was just a swell kid
with hot ideas who was in over his head.

1128
01:16:48,230 --> 01:16:50,150
Now your head's too big to be in over!

1129
01:16:50,357 --> 01:16:52,817
MAN: Hey.
- Consider this my resignation.

1130
01:16:53,277 --> 01:16:54,277
[GROANS]

1131
01:16:54,486 --> 01:16:56,106
Effective immediately!

1132
01:16:57,698 --> 01:16:59,408
[DOOR SLAMS]

1133
01:18:15,942 --> 01:18:18,532
BUZZ:
<i>Buddy, buddy.</i>

1134
01:18:18,737 --> 01:18:20,907
Buddy.

1135
01:18:21,114 --> 01:18:23,914
Buddy. Buddy, say, buddy.

1136
01:18:25,619 --> 01:18:27,449
Buddy, say, buddy.

1137
01:18:27,996 --> 01:18:31,376
Uh... Huh?

1138
01:18:31,583 --> 01:18:33,253
Buddy. You busy?

1139
01:18:33,794 --> 01:18:34,804
Huh?

1140
01:18:35,003 --> 01:18:38,223
Looks like you nodded off there, buddy.
Say, you got a minute?

1141
01:18:40,634 --> 01:18:41,934
Buzz?

1142
01:18:42,135 --> 01:18:43,425
Is this important?

1143
01:18:43,637 --> 01:18:46,767
I think so. It's this little idea
I've been working on.

1144
01:18:46,973 --> 01:18:49,433
You see, I don't intend
to be an elevator boy forever.

1145
01:18:49,643 --> 01:18:51,103
Take a look at this sweet baby!

1146
01:18:51,311 --> 01:18:53,611
Get it? Incredibly convenient, isn't it?

1147
01:18:53,814 --> 01:18:55,274
You know, for drinks?

1148
01:18:55,482 --> 01:18:57,692
This is how it works.
It's got these ridges...

1149
01:18:57,901 --> 01:18:59,611
...on the side that give it
its whammy.

1150
01:18:59,820 --> 01:19:03,370
See, you don't have to drink like this
anymore. You can drink like this.

1151
01:19:03,573 --> 01:19:06,083
I call it the Buzz-Sucker.
You get it, buddy?

1152
01:19:06,284 --> 01:19:09,504
People are dying for this
and we won't have to charge an arm an--

1153
01:19:09,705 --> 01:19:11,115
Wait a minute.

1154
01:19:11,331 --> 01:19:13,131
Shh.

1155
01:19:26,263 --> 01:19:27,813
This...

1156
01:19:30,100 --> 01:19:31,270
...is worthless!

1157
01:19:31,476 --> 01:19:33,056
Huh? But, buddy...

1158
01:19:33,270 --> 01:19:35,270
This is the most idiotic thing
I've ever seen.

1159
01:19:35,480 --> 01:19:36,480
Yeah, but, buddy--

1160
01:19:36,690 --> 01:19:38,730
Nobody wants a harebrained product
like this.

1161
01:19:38,942 --> 01:19:42,112
You see, Buzz,
it lacks the creative spark...

1162
01:19:42,320 --> 01:19:45,570
...the unalloyed genius
that made something like, say...

1163
01:19:45,782 --> 01:19:47,912
...the, uh, Hula-Hoop such a success.

1164
01:19:48,118 --> 01:19:50,368
What do you mean barging in
and taking up my time?

1165
01:19:50,579 --> 01:19:52,119
I've got a company to run here!

1166
01:19:52,330 --> 01:19:53,540
[LAUGHS]

1167
01:19:53,749 --> 01:19:55,499
- But, buddy--
- I can't have every deadbeat...

1168
01:19:55,709 --> 01:19:58,709
...on the payroll pestering me
with their idiotic brainwaves.

1169
01:19:58,920 --> 01:20:00,340
I'm sorry, buddy.

1170
01:20:00,547 --> 01:20:02,917
- An example must be made.
- What do you mean, buddy?

1171
01:20:04,634 --> 01:20:06,344
You're fired.

1172
01:20:06,553 --> 01:20:08,643
Is that plain enough for you, buster?

1173
01:20:08,930 --> 01:20:10,930
[SOBBING]

1174
01:20:13,894 --> 01:20:15,444
Oh, buddy!

1175
01:20:16,188 --> 01:20:18,188
And don't call me "buddy."

1176
01:20:18,398 --> 01:20:22,858
Oh, please, sir!
This job running the elevator, it's all I got!

1177
01:20:23,069 --> 01:20:24,779
Uh, it's okay if you don't like it.

1178
01:20:24,988 --> 01:20:28,368
Just let me keep my job,
I'm praying to you.

1179
01:20:28,575 --> 01:20:32,905
Get out of my office! Get up! Up!

1180
01:20:33,121 --> 01:20:35,921
We don't crawl here
at Hudsucker Industries!

1181
01:20:37,417 --> 01:20:40,877
BUZZ:
I'm sorry, sir! I'm sorry!

1182
01:20:42,088 --> 01:20:44,048
[BUZZ CONTINUES SOBBING]

1183
01:20:54,351 --> 01:20:56,941
MUSSBURGER:
Thank you, Aloysius.

1184
01:21:00,899 --> 01:21:03,189
This is...

1185
01:21:04,027 --> 01:21:05,737
...useful.

1186
01:21:19,918 --> 01:21:21,418
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

1187
01:21:23,296 --> 01:21:28,006
Sorry I'm late, Sid.
That back nine at Riverdale's really murder.

1188
01:21:28,802 --> 01:21:31,932
MUSSBURGER:
It's a tough course. A real lollapalooza.

1189
01:21:33,139 --> 01:21:34,219
Sit down, son.

1190
01:21:37,644 --> 01:21:42,614
I thought the boardroom would be
a swell place to chat undisturbed.

1191
01:21:43,024 --> 01:21:47,154
Seems we've got some security
problems here at the Hud.

1192
01:21:47,362 --> 01:21:48,782
You don't say.

1193
01:21:48,989 --> 01:21:51,239
MUSSBURGER:
Ordinarily, I wouldn't bother you with it...

1194
01:21:51,449 --> 01:21:53,619
...but this is embarrassing.

1195
01:21:54,286 --> 01:21:56,406
It concerns you directly.

1196
01:21:56,621 --> 01:21:59,251
- How's that, Sid?
- It's not serious in itself.

1197
01:21:59,916 --> 01:22:03,086
Some elevator boy
that you'd fired came to me...

1198
01:22:03,295 --> 01:22:07,255
...claiming that you'd stolen the idea
for, um, the dingus.

1199
01:22:07,465 --> 01:22:09,425
You'd stolen it from him.

1200
01:22:09,634 --> 01:22:10,974
[MUMBLES]

1201
01:22:12,220 --> 01:22:14,720
- Maybe I was a little rough on him--
- Forget it.

1202
01:22:14,931 --> 01:22:18,231
You don't have to explain to me.
He's a little person. He's nothing.

1203
01:22:18,435 --> 01:22:19,805
Fire whoever you want.

1204
01:22:21,855 --> 01:22:25,975
No, the problem is who you hired.

1205
01:22:26,192 --> 01:22:30,032
That dame. A spy, as it turns out.

1206
01:22:30,238 --> 01:22:33,698
She must have gotten
to that elevator schnook...

1207
01:22:33,909 --> 01:22:37,039
...and her paper is going to town.

1208
01:22:37,245 --> 01:22:42,665
Sure, sure, we tried to kill the story,
but the <i>Argus</i> won't play ball.

1209
01:22:43,209 --> 01:22:45,999
The problem the board
will have is you hired this woman...

1210
01:22:46,212 --> 01:22:48,842
...and you kept her on...

1211
01:22:49,049 --> 01:22:51,839
...while she was making a chump
out of you.

1212
01:22:52,052 --> 01:22:54,602
Serious error in judgment.

1213
01:22:55,388 --> 01:22:57,598
Business is war, kid.

1214
01:22:57,807 --> 01:23:00,847
Take no prisoners,
give no second chances.

1215
01:23:04,314 --> 01:23:06,864
When the board meets
after New Year's...

1216
01:23:07,067 --> 01:23:08,987
...your position...

1217
01:23:11,363 --> 01:23:13,203
Looks like you're finished.

1218
01:23:13,698 --> 01:23:15,278
Washed up.

1219
01:23:19,412 --> 01:23:22,792
Oh, fourteenth hole at Riverdale...

1220
01:23:22,999 --> 01:23:26,959
...some use a mashie,
some use a niblick.

1221
01:23:27,170 --> 01:23:28,760
Niblick.

1222
01:23:28,964 --> 01:23:31,224
You get more loft, more backspin.

1223
01:23:36,429 --> 01:23:37,969
That dame...

1224
01:23:38,807 --> 01:23:41,887
...she got your throat pretty well slit.

1225
01:23:42,102 --> 01:23:44,062
When you're dead, you stay dead.

1226
01:23:45,271 --> 01:23:48,191
You don't believe me,
ask Waring Hudsucker.

1227
01:23:49,859 --> 01:23:54,239
Tough luck, kid.
You had a short climb up.

1228
01:23:54,656 --> 01:23:56,776
It's a long way down.

1229
01:24:07,419 --> 01:24:09,419
AMY: Stolen hoop idea from--
You can't print that!

1230
01:24:09,629 --> 01:24:10,629
AL:
We are printing it!

1231
01:24:10,839 --> 01:24:12,969
She hits the streets this evening.

1232
01:24:13,174 --> 01:24:15,054
And she's dynamite!

1233
01:24:15,260 --> 01:24:16,430
But, Al, it's the bunk!

1234
01:24:16,636 --> 01:24:19,176
Norville showed me his design
the, uh, day I met him.

1235
01:24:19,389 --> 01:24:22,229
Buzz couldn't have invented it.
Look at him, he's an imbecile.

1236
01:24:22,434 --> 01:24:24,854
Aren't you a broken record?
Gunderson did design it.

1237
01:24:25,061 --> 01:24:26,441
Apparently, he's a prodigy.

1238
01:24:26,646 --> 01:24:28,856
- Says who?
- You're not the only one with sources.

1239
01:24:29,065 --> 01:24:31,565
Smith has a source on the Hud board.
Very hush-hush.

1240
01:24:31,776 --> 01:24:34,106
Yeah. I bet his initials
are Sidney J. Mussburger.

1241
01:24:34,320 --> 01:24:37,200
You lost it, Amy.
You gone soft, by the looks of it.

1242
01:24:37,407 --> 01:24:39,077
Soft on the dummy from Dubuque.

1243
01:24:40,118 --> 01:24:41,368
- Muncie.
AL: Whatever!

1244
01:24:41,578 --> 01:24:45,368
This story's hot and you're no longer on
top of it. It's the scoop of the century!

1245
01:24:45,582 --> 01:24:47,672
The other papers
won't have this till tomorrow!

1246
01:24:47,876 --> 01:24:51,626
They'll be choking on our dust
come morning.

1247
01:24:51,838 --> 01:24:55,298
You're fools, both of you!
You're being used, don't you see, ugh?

1248
01:24:55,508 --> 01:24:58,678
Take a break. You worked hard
on this story. You broke it for us.

1249
01:24:58,887 --> 01:25:01,927
But it's passed you by
and Smith's taking up the slack.

1250
01:25:02,974 --> 01:25:06,314
Tsk, oh, you want slack,
I'll give you slack!

1251
01:25:06,519 --> 01:25:10,319
You're not putting me out to pasture!
I quit! Consider this my resignation!

1252
01:25:10,523 --> 01:25:11,903
[BANGS]

1253
01:25:12,108 --> 01:25:14,318
Effective immediately!

1254
01:25:16,571 --> 01:25:18,411
Soft.

1255
01:25:27,040 --> 01:25:28,790
BRONFENBRENNER [OVER SPEAKER]:
<i>So tell me...</i>

1256
01:25:29,000 --> 01:25:31,750
<i>...why do you feel
this woman betrayed you?</i>

1257
01:25:31,961 --> 01:25:35,341
<i>Tsk, oh, what's the difference?</i>

1258
01:25:35,548 --> 01:25:38,298
<i>The whole world,
it seems, is against you?</i>

1259
01:25:38,510 --> 01:25:39,640
<i>I don't know.</i>

1260
01:25:39,844 --> 01:25:41,684
<i>Und the elevator boy...</i>

1261
01:25:41,888 --> 01:25:45,058
<i>...Buzz, he too works against you?</i>

1262
01:25:45,266 --> 01:25:46,976
<i>NORVILLE:
Well, yeah.</i>

1263
01:25:47,185 --> 01:25:48,345
Classic.

1264
01:25:48,561 --> 01:25:51,771
Patient displayed listlessness,
apathy, gloomy indifference...

1265
01:25:51,981 --> 01:25:54,031
<i>...und was blue und mopey.</i>

1266
01:25:54,234 --> 01:25:57,454
When asked what the Rorschach stains
represented, patient replied:

1267
01:25:57,946 --> 01:26:02,656
"Nothing much. I don't know.
Just a blotch. Sure beats me."

1268
01:26:02,867 --> 01:26:06,447
Patient shows no ambition,
no get-up-and-go, no vim.

1269
01:26:06,663 --> 01:26:09,173
He is riding the grand loopen-ze-loop...

1270
01:26:09,374 --> 01:26:12,214
...that goes from the height
of delusional gaiety...

1271
01:26:12,418 --> 01:26:14,498
...to the trough of despair.

1272
01:26:14,712 --> 01:26:17,882
He is now near,
but not yet at his lowest point.

1273
01:26:18,091 --> 01:26:23,971
<i>When he reaches bottom, he may erupt
und pose a danger to himself und others.</i>

1274
01:26:24,180 --> 01:26:26,060
MUSSBURGER:
Diagnosis, Dr. Bronfenbrenner?

1275
01:26:26,266 --> 01:26:29,226
Patient is eine manic-depressive
paranoid, type B...

1276
01:26:29,435 --> 01:26:31,305
...with acute schizoid tendencies.

1277
01:26:31,521 --> 01:26:34,521
So patient is...?

1278
01:26:35,275 --> 01:26:37,685
Precisely, nuts!

1279
01:26:38,278 --> 01:26:39,318
Prescription?

1280
01:26:39,529 --> 01:26:44,489
Three things, commitment,
electroconvulsive therapy...

1281
01:26:44,701 --> 01:26:48,161
...maintenance in <i>eine</i> secure facility.

1282
01:26:48,830 --> 01:26:50,750
[ALL APPLAUDING]

1283
01:27:02,969 --> 01:27:05,759
MAN:
Yeah, he's a tall guy. A real mess.

1284
01:27:05,972 --> 01:27:10,352
Yeah, yeah, look, you better get down here.
He says he's a friend of yours.

1285
01:27:10,560 --> 01:27:14,270
He didn't say.
But, man, is he from Squaresville.

1286
01:27:16,441 --> 01:27:18,611
[NORVILLE TALKS INDISTINCTLY]

1287
01:27:18,818 --> 01:27:20,568
[BLOWS HORN]

1288
01:27:22,071 --> 01:27:23,621
NORVILLE:
I want a martini!

1289
01:27:23,823 --> 01:27:26,623
It's New Year's Eve. I deserve a martini.

1290
01:27:26,826 --> 01:27:31,116
- Daddy, it's like I've been telling you. You--
- I thought you served misfits here.

1291
01:27:31,331 --> 01:27:34,131
Yeah, daddy. That's a roger.
But we don't sell alcohol.

1292
01:27:34,334 --> 01:27:36,794
What kind of bar is it,
you can't get a martini?

1293
01:27:37,003 --> 01:27:40,473
It's a juice-and-coffee bar, man,
like I've been telling you.

1294
01:27:40,673 --> 01:27:45,723
- Right. So I want a martini.
- Argh.

1295
01:27:45,929 --> 01:27:49,309
I've had a martini in every bar
all the way down here, heh.

1296
01:27:49,515 --> 01:27:51,975
Martinis are for squares, man.

1297
01:27:53,436 --> 01:27:56,396
What'd you call me,
you beatnik son of a--?

1298
01:27:56,606 --> 01:27:57,606
AMY:
Norville.

1299
01:27:59,609 --> 01:28:00,779
What?

1300
01:28:00,985 --> 01:28:05,405
- Oh-ho, look who's here, Amy Archer...
- Oh, no.

1301
01:28:05,615 --> 01:28:07,775
...Prizeter Pule winner.

1302
01:28:07,992 --> 01:28:10,082
Looking for a nitwit to buy you lunch?

1303
01:28:10,286 --> 01:28:13,956
- Norville, I'm sorry.
- Bar fella, I'd like...

1304
01:28:14,165 --> 01:28:15,165
...a martini, please.

1305
01:28:15,375 --> 01:28:18,995
I tried to tell you so many times, I...

1306
01:28:19,212 --> 01:28:23,222
It's hard to admit
when you've been wrong.

1307
01:28:23,424 --> 01:28:25,054
If you could just...

1308
01:28:25,260 --> 01:28:29,890
...find it in your heart
to give me another chance.

1309
01:28:30,974 --> 01:28:31,984
Ha.

1310
01:28:32,183 --> 01:28:34,443
"You take no prisoners,
give no second chances."

1311
01:28:34,644 --> 01:28:38,024
Please, Norville!
Please give me one more chance!

1312
01:28:38,231 --> 01:28:41,651
And yourself too. We both deserve one.

1313
01:28:41,859 --> 01:28:43,189
Just give us a second chance.

1314
01:28:43,403 --> 01:28:45,363
Together we can fight this thing.

1315
01:28:45,571 --> 01:28:47,991
I know this last story was a lie
and we can prove it.

1316
01:28:48,199 --> 01:28:49,529
You got to release a statement.

1317
01:28:49,742 --> 01:28:53,252
- I can help you write it.
- Oh, what's the difference?

1318
01:28:53,454 --> 01:28:55,624
I'm all washed up.

1319
01:28:55,832 --> 01:28:59,882
<i>Extinct. Homo sapiens sapicus.</i>

1320
01:29:00,086 --> 01:29:01,046
[HICCUPPING]

1321
01:29:01,254 --> 01:29:05,684
Well, heh, that just about does it.

1322
01:29:05,883 --> 01:29:09,513
I've seen Norville Barnes,
the young man in a big hurry...

1323
01:29:09,721 --> 01:29:13,221
...and I've seen Norville Barnes,
the self-important heel.

1324
01:29:13,433 --> 01:29:16,563
But I've never seen Norville Barnes,
the quitter...

1325
01:29:17,270 --> 01:29:19,400
...and I don't like it.

1326
01:29:20,440 --> 01:29:22,400
Fight on.

1327
01:29:22,608 --> 01:29:26,358
Fight on, dear old Muncie.

1328
01:29:27,071 --> 01:29:31,531
Fight on. Hoist the gold and blue.

1329
01:29:31,743 --> 01:29:35,463
You'll be tattered, torn and hurting.

1330
01:29:35,663 --> 01:29:40,423
Once the Munce is done with you.

1331
01:29:41,627 --> 01:29:44,837
Go, Eagles.

1332
01:29:46,924 --> 01:29:49,394
You can't surrender, Norville.
Remember.

1333
01:29:50,762 --> 01:29:55,772
<i>[SINGING] Fight on, Fight on
Dear old Muncie</i>

1334
01:29:55,975 --> 01:29:56,975
[SOBBING]

1335
01:29:57,185 --> 01:30:02,355
<i>Fight on
Hoist the gold and blue</i>

1336
01:30:03,316 --> 01:30:07,106
<i>You'll be tattered, torn and hurting</i>

1337
01:30:08,946 --> 01:30:12,906
You lied to me. How could you lie to me?

1338
01:30:14,744 --> 01:30:18,414
You, a Muncie girl.

1339
01:30:19,707 --> 01:30:22,417
But, Norville, I...

1340
01:30:22,627 --> 01:30:28,967
When you're dead, you stay dead.
Just ask Waring Hudsucker!

1341
01:30:30,218 --> 01:30:32,468
Oh, Norville.

1342
01:30:32,678 --> 01:30:34,718
[SOB5]

1343
01:30:35,264 --> 01:30:38,644
NEWSBOY:
Extra, extra! New Year's Eve edition!

1344
01:30:38,851 --> 01:30:41,231
Barnes' brain caught red-handed!

1345
01:30:41,437 --> 01:30:43,017
Ideas ersatz!

1346
01:30:43,231 --> 01:30:46,151
Man from Muncie a moron after all!

1347
01:30:46,359 --> 01:30:48,439
Read all about it!

1348
01:30:48,653 --> 01:30:52,993
New Year's Eve edition!
Man from Muncie a moron after all!

1349
01:30:53,199 --> 01:30:55,159
You're not so slow,
but you're not so swell.

1350
01:30:55,368 --> 01:30:57,498
And it looks like
you're an imbecile after all.

1351
01:30:57,703 --> 01:31:00,833
Sure, sure.
But your friends called you dope?

1352
01:31:01,040 --> 01:31:03,210
Dipstick? Lamebrain? Schmo?

1353
01:31:03,418 --> 01:31:06,418
Please, buddy, running the elevator,
it's all I got.

1354
01:31:06,629 --> 01:31:08,589
<i>EISENHOWER:
Norville, you let me down.</i>

1355
01:31:08,798 --> 01:31:13,088
<i>You let Mrs. Eisenhower down.
You let the American people down.</i>

1356
01:31:13,302 --> 01:31:15,682
- And when you're dead, you stay dead.
AMY: Ha-ha-ha.

1357
01:31:15,888 --> 01:31:19,178
You stay dead, you stay dead.
Sure, sure.

1358
01:31:19,392 --> 01:31:22,442
The kid is screwy, it's official.

1359
01:31:23,062 --> 01:31:26,192
The barred-window boys
are out looking for him now.

1360
01:31:26,399 --> 01:31:28,359
We'll see how Wall Street
likes the news...

1361
01:31:28,568 --> 01:31:31,818
...that the president of Hudsucker
is headed for the booby hatch.

1362
01:31:32,029 --> 01:31:36,329
Heh, when Doc Bronfenbrenner
gets through with him...

1363
01:31:36,534 --> 01:31:38,544
...he'll need diapers and a dribble cup.

1364
01:31:38,744 --> 01:31:39,754
[ALL CHUCKLE]

1365
01:31:39,954 --> 01:31:42,374
Well, if that's all...

1366
01:31:42,582 --> 01:31:45,462
ALL:
Long live the Hud!

1367
01:31:47,628 --> 01:31:49,588
[UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING IN DISTANCE]

1368
01:31:53,426 --> 01:31:54,386
[ALL GRUNT]

1369
01:31:54,594 --> 01:31:57,974
Watch where you're-- Hiya, buddy!

1370
01:31:58,181 --> 01:32:00,311
- Buzz?
- Out on the town, huh? Guess what?

1371
01:32:00,516 --> 01:32:05,476
Sid says I can have my old job back.
I deserve a second chance, he says.

1372
01:32:05,688 --> 01:32:08,978
- Huh? He did?
- Turns out he's not such a bad guy after all.

1373
01:32:09,192 --> 01:32:10,862
- Ha, ha.
- Buzz, that's wonderful.

1374
01:32:11,068 --> 01:32:14,908
He told me you stole that swell hoop idea
from me. What gives?

1375
01:32:15,114 --> 01:32:18,954
- Buzz, I would never--
- Gee, that was a swell idea.

1376
01:32:19,160 --> 01:32:21,290
And Sid says you stoled it!

1377
01:32:21,496 --> 01:32:23,866
What are you waiting on, Clarence?
Pop him one.

1378
01:32:24,081 --> 01:32:25,751
But Buzz--

1379
01:32:26,501 --> 01:32:27,501
[NORVILLE GROANS]

1380
01:32:28,961 --> 01:32:30,211
[CROWD MURMURING]

1381
01:32:34,759 --> 01:32:36,009
He's that big-shot faker!

1382
